# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alligator-hunting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Under the terms of the 1986 moratorium, the International Whaling Commission allows the activity to be carried out by aboriginal groups if it occurs on a subsistence basis, similar to subsistence fishing.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] This **Aboriginal Subsistence Whaling** is restricted to native peoples and others working on their behalf, as defined by the IWC.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Since its inception, the IWC has recognised that indigenous or 'aboriginal subsistence' whaling is of a different nature to commercial whaling.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] It is thus not subject to the moratorium.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] This is reflected in the different objectives for the two types of whaling.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] In order for a country to carry out a hunt under the aboriginal group clause, the nation must provide the IWC with evidence of "the cultural and subsistence needs of their people." In particular, the hunt is not intended for commercial purposes and the caught meat cannot be exported.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] In 2018, the Commission endorsed proposals made by a working group established six-years earlier to consider some long-standing and complex questions, and improve the way that the Commission considered ASW.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] A number of new initiatives were endorsed in order to facilitate a more straight-forward process when catch limits are next considered at the 2024 meeting of the Commission.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] In the United States whaling is carried out by Alaska Natives and by the Makah of Washington State.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] It no longer occurs on the Atlantic coast, although the Pilgrim Fathers found the original inhabitants of New England had a well-developed understanding of drift whales.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The Arctic whaling program is managed by the Alaska Eskimo Whaling Commission, which reports to the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The commission includes eleven whaling communities which inhabit the Arctic Alaska coast: the Gambell, Savoonga, Wales, Little Diomede, Kivalina, Point Hope, Point Lay, Wainwright, Barrow, Nuiqsut, and Kaktovik.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] In 2015 Alaska Natives caught 326 beluga whales and 49 bowhead whales.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] In 2016 they caught 59 bowhead whales, two minke and one humpback whale; The latter two species were not authorized, though no one was prosecuted.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Annual catches vary between 300 and 500 belugas and 40 to 70 bowheads.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The hunt takes the bowhead whales from a population of about 10,000 in Alaskan waters.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Anti-whaling groups claim this hunt is not sustainable, though the IWC Scientific Committee, the same group that provided the above population estimate, projects a population growth of 3.2% per year.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The hunt also took an average of one or two gray whales each year until 1996.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The quota was reduced to zero in that year due to concerns about sustainability.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] According to federal law, the Makah people of Washington State are entitled to hunt and kill one baleen whale, typically a gray whale, each year, though archeological records and oral history indicate a significant number of humpback whales were hunted as well.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The Makah ended their whaling practices in the 1920s, but notified the U.S.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Government of their wish to reassert their whaling rights in 1995.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The first permitted Makah whale hunt in 70 years occurred on 17 May 1999, when they caught a north Pacific gray whale, an unpermitted hunt killed another in 2007, and in 2018 they took meat from a humpback killed by a ship strike.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] An environmental impact statement for further hunts was issued in 2015.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] On 5 April 2019 NOAA Fisheries proposed issuing a waiver under the MMPA to the Makah tribe to allow hunting, as well as a what stakeholders can do to engage in the public rule making process before an Administrative Law Judge.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] One of the main stipulations that NOAA proposed was allowing the Makah people to hunt as many as 20 gray whales every five years, however prior to any hunt the tribe would have to obtain a permit from NOAA.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] On 2 August 2019 the Administrative Law Judge announced that the final agenda for the hearing on NOAA's proposed waiver and regulations was set for November 2019, which was postponed from the previous 26 June 2019 announcement.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Canada left the IWC in 1982 and as such is not bound by the moratorium.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Whaling is carried out by various Inuit groups in the Canadian Arctic in small numbers and is managed by the Department of Fisheries and Oceans.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Chukchi people of the Chukotka Autonomous Okrug in the Russian Far East are permitted to take up to 140 gray whales from the North-East Pacific population and 67 Bering-Chukchi-Beaufort bowhead whales in the period 2026 - 2031.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Some whaling is conducted from Grenada, Dominica, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines and Saint Lucia.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Species hunted are the short-finned pilot whale, killer whale, pygmy killer whale and spinner dolphins.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Throughout the Caribbean, around 400 pilot whales are killed annually with the meat being sold locally.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] This hunting of small cetaceans is not regulated by the IWC.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Whales are hunted in Bequia, the largest of the Grenadines.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Natives of Bequia are allowed to catch up to four humpback whales per year using only traditional hunting methods of hand-thrown harpoons in small, open sailboats.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The limit is rarely met, with no catch some years.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Its classification as aboriginal, and therefore permissible, is highly contested.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] In the 2012 meeting of the IWC, delegates from several anti-whaling countries, and environmental groups, spoke out against it, with Peter Sanchez of the Dominican Republic calling it "artisanal whaling out of control".
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Whalers in the Faroe Islands take approximately 800 long-finned pilot whales per year.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] These hunts are called *grindadráp* in Faroese.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Lamalera, on the south coast of the island of Lembata, and Lamakera on neighbouring Solor are the last two remaining Indonesian whaling communities.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The hunters have religious taboos that ensure that they use every part of the animal.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] About half of the catch is kept in the village; the rest is traded in local markets, using barter.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The whale hunts are carried out in a traditional manner, with bamboo spears and small wooden outriggers, 10–12 m long and 2m wide, constructed without nails and with sails woven from palm fronds.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The animals are killed by the harpooner leaping onto the back of the animal, from the boat, to drive in the harpoon.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The people of Lamalera hunt several species of whales, primarily sperm whales (the baleen whale is taboo), and in the peak year of 1969 caught 56 sperm whales.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] In addition to whales, dolphins, manta rays, turtles and several species of sharks are also hunted.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] In 1973, the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization sent a whaling ship and a Norwegian master whaler, to modernize the hunt.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] This effort lasted three years, and was not successful.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The World Wildlife Fund has carried out surveys in the village to determine that the limited hunting does not endanger world whale stocks or other endangered species.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Commercial whaling and poachers hunt whales in large quantities and sell them illegally.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] The International Whaling Commission (IWC) does not allow the hunting of any whales except for aboriginal subsistence whaling and scientific whaling, which have catch limits to maintain the conservation of whales.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] These groups must report their hunts and the number of whales killed in order to track the population of whale species and conservation.
[src:alligator-hunting/aboriginal-whaling] Hunting illegally means the kills are not reported, which makes it difficult to maintain population numbers and conservation.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] An **air gun** or **airgun** is a gun that uses compressed air or other pressurized gases to fire projectiles, reminiscent of the principle behind the ancient blowgun.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] This is in contrast to a firearm, which shoots projectiles using pressure generated via combustion of a chemical propellant, most often black powder in antique firearms and smokeless powder in modern firearms.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Air guns come in both long gun (**air rifle**) and handgun (**air pistol**) forms.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Both types typically propel metallic projectiles that are either diabolo-shaped pellets or spherical shots called BBs, although in recent years Minié ball-shaped cylindro-conoidal projectiles called slugs are becoming more popular.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Certain types of air guns (usually air rifles) may also launch fin-stabilized projectile such as darts (e.g., tranquilizer guns) or hollow-shafted arrows (so-called "airbows").
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The air guns were first developed in the 16th century, and have since been used in hunting, shooting sports, and even in warfare.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] There are three different power sources for modern air guns, depending on the design: spring-piston, pneumatic or bottled compressed gas (most commonly carbon dioxide and recently nitrogen).
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Air guns represent the oldest pneumatic technology.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The oldest existing mechanical air gun dates back to about 1580, and is currently kept in the Livrustkammaren Museum in Stockholm.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] This is approximately what most historians recognize as the beginning of the modern air gun.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Throughout 17th to 19th century, air guns in .30 to .51 calibers were used to hunt big game, deer and wild boar.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] These air rifles were charged using a pump to fill an air reservoir and produced velocities from 650 to 1,000 ft/s (200 to 300 m/s).
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] They were also used in warfare, the most recognized example being the Girandoni air rifle, a repeating rifle used by Austria in the 1788 war against Turkey.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] At that time, they had compelling advantages over the muzzleloader firearms of the day.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] For example, air guns could be discharged in wet weather and rain (unlike both matchlock and flintlock muskets), and discharged much faster than muzzle-loading guns.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Moreover, they were quieter than a firearm of a similar caliber and produced no muzzle flash or smoke cloud when fired.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Thus, they did not give away the shooter's position or obscure the shooter's view, unlike the black powder muskets of the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] In the hands of skilled soldiers, they gave the military a distinct advantage.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] France, Austria and other nations had special sniper detachments using air rifles, mostly Jäger (infantry).
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The Austrian 1779 model was named *Windbüchse* (literally "wind rifle" in German).
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The gun was developed in 1768 or 1769 by the Tyrolean Ladins watchmaker, mechanic and gunsmith Bartholomäus Girardoni (1744–1799) and is sometimes referred to as the Girandoni air rifle or Girardoni air gun in literature (the name is also spelled "Girandony", "Giradoni" or "Girardoni".).
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Adopted by the Austrian leadership in 1779, the *Windbüchse* was about 4 ft (1.2 m) long and weighed 10 pounds (4.5 kg), about the same size and mass as a conventional musket.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The air reservoir was a removable, club-shaped, butt.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The *Windbüchse* carried twenty-two .51 caliber (13 mm) lead balls in a tubular magazine.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] A skilled shooter could fire off one magazine in about thirty seconds.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] A shot from this air gun could penetrate a one-inch-thick (2.5 cm) wooden board at a hundred paces, an effect roughly equal to that of a modern 9×19mm or .45 ACP caliber pistol.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Circa 1820, the Japanese inventor Kunitomo Ikkansai developed various manufacturing methods for guns, and also created an air gun based on the study of Western knowledge ("rangaku") acquired from the Dutch in Dejima.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The Lewis and Clark Expedition (1804) carried a reservoir air gun, very likely the Girardoni, as it held 22 round balls of .46 caliber in a tubular magazine mounted on the side of the barrel.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The butt of the gun served as the air reservoir and had a working pressure of 800 psi (55 bar).
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The rifle was said to be capable of 22 aimed shots per minute and had a rifled bore of 0.452 in (11.5 mm) and a groove diameter 0.462 in (11.7 mm).
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] One of the first commercially successful and mass-produced air guns was manufactured by the William F.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Markham's Markham Air Rifle Company in Plymouth, Michigan, US.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Their first model air gun was the wooden *Challenger*, marketed in 1886.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] In response, Clarence Hamilton from the neighboring Plymouth Air Rifle Company (later renamed to Daisy Manufacturing Company in 1895) marketed their all-metal Daisy BB Gun in early 1888, which prompted Markham to respond with their *Chicago* model in 1888 followed by the *King* model in 1890.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The *Chicago* model was sold by Sears, Roebuck for 73 cents in its catalog.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] In 1928, the name of the Markham company was changed to King Air Rifle Company after the company was purchased by Daisy in 1916 after decades of intense competition, and continued to manufacture the "King" model air rifle until 1935 before ceasing operation altogether in the 1940s.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] From the 1890s onwards, air rifles were used in Birmingham, England for competitive target shooting.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Matches were held in public houses and working men's clubs, which sponsored shooting teams.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] This often took the form of Bell Target shooting, where the competitor aims to ring a bell by shooting through a small hole in a steel plate.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Prizes, such as a leg of mutton for the winning team, were paid for by the losing team.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] During this time, over 4,000 air rifle clubs and associations existed across Great Britain, with as many as 1,600 in Birmingham alone.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] During this time, the air gun was associated with poaching because it could deliver a shot without a significant muzzle report.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Air guns are used for hunting (small to medium game), pest control, recreational shooting (commonly known as plinking) and competitive sports such as the Olympic 10 m air rifle and 10 m air pistol events.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Field target (FT) is a competitive form of metallic silhouette shooting in which the targets are animal-shaped steel targets with a "kill zone" cut-out.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Hunter field target (HFT) is a variation, using identical equipment, but with differing rules.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The distances FT and HFT competitions are shot at range between 7.3 and 41.1 metres (24 and 135 ft) for HFT & 7.3 and 50.29 metres (24.0 and 165.0 ft) for FT, with varying sizes of "reducers" being used to increase or decrease the size of the kill zone.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] In the UK, competition power limits are set at the legal maximum for an unlicensed air rifle, i.e.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Air rifle benchrest is an international shooting sport where the objective is to hit a (small) bulls eye target at 25 m (27.34 yd) shooting distance.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] There are two divisions ARLV 12 ft⋅lbf (16.27 J) and ARHV 20 ft⋅lbf (27.12 J).
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The increasing affordability of higher-power pre-charged pneumatic (PCP) rifles has allowed large projectiles and further target distance for competition purposes.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] For instance, the Extreme Benchrest competition held annually in Green Valley, Arizona allows calibers up to .30 inches (7.6 mm) at 75 yd (68.58 m) while the Big Bore Benchrest arm of the same competition at other localities engages targets at 35 to 300 yards (32 to 274 m).
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The component of an airgun that provides the gas pressure needed to propel projectiles is called its *powerplant*, which uses internally stored pressurized gas; and *compressed gas* (most commonly CO2), which uses external sources of pressurized gas.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] A **spring-piston air gun** (also known as a **spring gun** or simply a "**springer**") operates by means of a spring-loaded piston pump assembly contained within a compression chamber separate from the gun barrel.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Traditionally, a grease-lubricated steel coil spring is used as the powerplant main spring.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Before shooting, the user needs to manually cock the gun by flexing a lever connected to the pump assembly, which pulls the pump piston rearwards and compresses the main spring until the rear of the piston engages the sear.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] When shooting, the trigger is pulled and disengages the sear, allowing the main spring to decompress and release its stored elastic potential energy, pushing the piston forward, thereby compressing the air in the pump cylinder.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] All this takes place in a fraction of a second, during which the air undergoes adiabatic heating to several hundred degrees and then cools as the air expands.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] This can also cause a phenomenon referred as "dieseling", where flammable substances in the compression chamber (e.g., petroleum-based lubricant) can be ignited by the compression heat like in a diesel engine, and lead to an afterburner effect with (often unpredictable) additional thrusts.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] This often results in combustion smoke coming out of the muzzle and potential pressure damage to the rubber O-ring seals inside the gun.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Dieseling can be made to occur *intentionally* to increase power, by coating the pellet with lubricant or petroleum jelly, although this may result in damage to the breech seal.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Most spring-piston guns are single-shot breechloaders by nature, but multiple-shot repeaters with magazine feeders have been introduced in recent years by manufacturers such as Gamo, Umarex and Hatsan.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Spring-piston guns, especially the high-powered "magnum" guns, are able to achieve muzzle velocities exceeding the speed of sound.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The effort required for the cocking stroke is proportional to the designed power of the gun, with higher muzzle velocities requiring a stiffer spring and hence a greater cocking effort.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Spring-piston guns have a practical upper limit of 1,250 ft/s (380 m/s) for .177 cal (4.5 mm) pellets, as higher velocities cause unstable pellet flight and loss of accuracy.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] This is due to the extreme buffeting caused when the pellet reaches and surpasses transonic speed, then slows back down and goes through sound barrier again, which is more than enough to destabilize the pellet's flight.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Shortly after leaving the barrel, the supersonic pellet falls back below the speed of sound and the shock wave overtakes the pellet, causing its flight stability to be disrupted.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Drag increases disproportionately as pellet velocity increases, so it is generally better to increase pellet weight to keep velocities subsonic in high-powered guns.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Many shooters find that velocities in the 800–900 ft/s (240–270 m/s) range offer an ideal balance between power and accuracy.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Spring-piston guns, especially high-powered ("magnum") models, do still recoil as a result of the mainspring pushing the piston forward.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Although the recoil is less than that of some cartridge firearms, it can make the gun difficult to shoot accurately as the spring recoil is in effect while the pellet is still within the barrel.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Spring gun recoil also has a sharp forward component, caused by the piston hitting the front end of the pump chamber when the spring has fully decompressed.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] These rapid double-jerking movements are known to damage scopes not rated for spring gun usage.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] In addition, the spring often has unpredictable collateral transverse vibrations as well as torquing, both of which can cause accuracy to suffer.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The better quality spring guns can have very long service lives, being simple to maintain and repair.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Because they deliver the same mechanical energy output on each shot, external ballistics are quite consistent.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Most Olympic air gun competitions through the 1970s and into the 1980s were shot with spring-piston guns, often of the opposing-piston recoil-eliminating type.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Beginning in the 1980s, guns powered by compressed/liquefied carbon dioxide began to dominate the competition.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Today, the guns used at the highest levels of competition are powered by compressed air.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Some newer generation air guns incorporate a gas spring (commonly referred to as a *gas piston*, *gas ram*, *gas strut* or *nitro piston*) instead of a mechanical spring.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The spring itself is essentially a stand-alone enclosed piston pump without outlets and with pressurized air or inert gas (such as nitrogen) held tightly sealed within the cylinder.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] When the gun is cocked, the gas inside the cylinder gets further compressed by the piston, stores potential energy and acts as a pneumatic accumulator.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Gas spring units require higher precision to manufacture since they require a low-friction sliding seal that can withstand the high pressures within when cocked.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Gas springs perform more reliably in cold climates than coil springs, because metallic coil springs need to be coated with lubricating grease which often thickens in low temperatures causing the gun to "freeze up".
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Gas springs also have less lateral and longitudinal vibrations than coil springs, hence are usually less "hold-sensitive", making it easier to achieve consistent shot groupings.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Pneumatic airguns propel the projectiles by utilizing the pneumatic potential energy within compressed air, which is pressurized beforehand and stored inside the gun, and then released through valves during shooting.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Single-stroke and multi-stroke pump guns utilize an on-board hand pump to pressurize air in an internal reservoir tank, while pre-charged pneumatic guns' reservoirs are filled from an external source using either a high-pressure stand pump or by decanting air from a larger diving cylinder.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Because of the need for cylinders or charging systems, PCP guns have higher initial costs but much lower operating costs when compared to CO2 rifles, and have superior performance over ordinary pump guns.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Having no significant movement of heavy mechanical parts during the discharge cycle, PCP airgun designs produce lower recoil, and can shoot as many as 100 shots per charge depending on the tank/reservoir size.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The ready supply of air has allowed the development of semi- and fully automatic air guns.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] PCP guns are very popular in Europe because of their accuracy and ease of use.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] They are widely utilized in ISSF 10 meter air pistol and rifle shooting events and the sport of Field Target shooting, and are usually fitted with telescopic sights.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Early stand pump designs encountered problems of fatigue (both human and mechanical), temperature warping, and condensation – none of which are beneficial to accurate shooting or the airguns' longevity.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Modern stand pumps have multi-stage chambers and built-in air filtration systems and have overcome many of these problems.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Using scuba-quality air decanted from a diving cylinder provides consistently clean, dry, high-pressure air.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] During the typical PCP's discharge cycle, the hammer of the rifle is released by the sear to strike the bash valve.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The hammer may move rearwards or forwards, unlike firearms where the hammer almost always moves forward.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The valve is held closed by a spring and the pressure of the air in the reservoir.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The pressure of the spring is constant, and the pressure of the air released (which is also known as the *working pressure*) decreases with each successive shot.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] As a result, when the reservoir pressure is high, the valve opens less fully and closes faster than when the reservoir pressure is lower, resulting in a similar total volume of air flowing past the valve with each shot.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] This results in a degree of partial self-regulation that gives a greater consistency of velocity from shot to shot, which corresponds to the middle "plateau" phase of the gun's shot-to-shot muzzle velocity profile (also known as the *power curve* ).
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Well-designed PCP will display good shot-to-shot consistency over a long period, as the air reservoir is being depleted.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Other PCP rifles and pistols are regulated, i.e. the firing valve operates within a secondary chamber separated from the main air reservoir by the regulator body.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The regulator maintains the pressure within this secondary chamber at a set pressure (lower than the main reservoir's) until the main reservoir's pressure drops to the point where it can no longer do so.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] As a result, shot-to-shot consistency is maintained for longer than in an unregulated rifle, and the gun can also output more shots due to reduced waste of reservoir pressure.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] CO2 guns are popular for training, as the guns and ammunition are inexpensive, relatively safe to use, and no specialized facilities are needed for safety.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] In addition, they can be purchased and owned in areas where firearms possession is either strictly controlled or banned outright.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Most CO2 powered guns are relatively inexpensive, and there are a few precision target guns available that use CO2.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The high-pressure air (HPA) system, or *N2*, was originally developed for paintball markers as a replacement for CO2 cartridges, and uses powerlet interface-compatible diving cylinders filled with either pure nitrogen or compressed air (which is 78% nitrogen).
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Because nitrogen is more inert than CO2, it remains in the gaseous state longer when compressed; when it expands, it cools due to the Joule-Thomson effect, but at a far lower rate than liquid CO2 because there is no change in state from liquid to gas.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] This thermostability reduces the variation in output pressure associated with rapid successions of firing cycles, improving accuracy and reliability in extreme climates.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] However, because compressed air is stored at higher pressures (up to 34 MPa or 4,900 psi) than liquid CO2 (stored at around 8 MPa or 1,200 psi), HPA cylinders are more expensive.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Cylinders smaller than 1.1 L (67 cu in) may not even last as long as a standard CO2 cartridge when subjected to frequent use.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] It is also possible to power an HPA-compatible gun directly from a plug-in air compressor without using a gas cylinder, though this type of setup is rare.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Each air cartridge is essentially a self-contained gas reservoir housed inside a cartridge case (usually in the size of a .38 Special), with an internal bash valve designed to release the content when the base of the cartridge is struck.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Prior to shooting, each cartridge is pre-filled with sufficient compressed air for one shot (typically via a multi-stroke hand pump) and has a .177/.22 caliber pellet pre-seated to its front slot, and the entire cartridge is then inserted into a chamber in the gun barrel.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] When shooting, the hammer hits the rear of the air cartridge, mimicking the function of a centerfire ammunition.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] This allows the airgun to be constructed and operated in similar fashions to genuine firearms.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] It also allows for higher shot consistency because each cartridge can be easily filled to an identical air charge, essentially removing the "power curve" of conventional PCP guns and bypassing any need for regulators.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] It also simplifies the magazine feed design and eliminates the risk of deforming the projectiles when the action seats each pellet, as the soft lead pellet is protected from contact with the action probe by the harder cartridge casing.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The air cartridge system, both in the rifle and revolver forms, was at the peak of its popularity throughout the 1990s.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The popularity of the Brocock range was such that, by 2002, estimates put the number of air cartridge guns in circulation around 70,000-80,000.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] However, a small number of incidents relating to the alleged illegal conversion of (mainly) Brococks to allow them to discharge live ammunition sparked a media frenzy.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] After the UK government implemented the Anti-social Behaviour Act 2003 in January 2004, it became illegal to possess such airguns without a firearm certificate in the United Kingdom.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Brocock subsequently ceased production of all air cartridge systems and turned to focus primarily on PCP airguns.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The most popular ammunition used in rifled air guns is made of lead, a heavy metal.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Lead is highly poisonous (whether inhaled or swallowed), affecting almost every organ and system in the human body.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] For this reason, lead-free pellets are becoming increasingly popular, and are available in all major shapes and styles, just like traditional lead pellets.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] In flight, the skirt has greater drag-to-weight ratio than the head and exerts a rearward pull behind the center of mass, similar to that of a shuttlecock.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] This produces a phenomenon known as *drag stabilization*, which helps to counteract yawing and maintain a consistent flight path.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] However, the diabolo shape also means that the overall pellet will have poor ballistic coefficient and tends to lose energy quickly and be more unstable especially in the transonic region (272–408 m/s ~ 893–1340 ft/s).
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Diabolo pellets are conventionally made from lead, but are widely available in non-lead alternatives, such as tin, or a combination of materials such as steel or gold alloys with polymer tips.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] A variety of lead-free pellets are offered by all major pellet manufacturers, including H&N Sport, RWS, JSB, Gamo, and others.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Since lead is very dense, it has a higher ballistic coefficient than lightweight alternatives such as tin, copper, or plastic.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] At the present time, the airgun industry does not mass-produce dense alternatives to lead with a high ballistic coefficient for long-range shooting.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Some manufacturers also have recently introduced the more cylindro-conoidal-shaped "slug" pellets for the more powerful modern PCP air rifles.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Appropriately sized bullets cast from firearm bullet molds can be used in big bore air rifles.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Caution should be used when handling lead projectiles or preparing animals for food, as lead fragments can be easily missed inside the meat.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Lead-free slugs in airgun calibers are gradually being developed and becoming available for purchase from manufacturers such as Zan Projectiles, due in part to regulations on hunting with lead projectiles in many areas.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The BB shot was once the most common airgun ammunition in the US, thanks to the popularity of Daisy's line of BB airguns.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] A BB is a small metallic ball in 4.5 mm/.177" diameter, typically made of steel (with a copper or zinc coating) or lead.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Originally called the "round shot", the contemporary name came from the "BB"- size lead birdshot used in shotgun shells, which the first BB gun invented in 1886 was designed to shoot.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Steel BBs can be acceptably accurate at short distances when fired from properly designed BB guns with smoothbore barrels.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Lead #3 buckshot pellets can be used in .25" caliber airguns as if they were large BBs.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Therefore, steel BBs lack the spin stabilization required for long-range accuracy, and usage in any but the cheapest rifled guns is discouraged.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The softer lead BBs, however, can be used in rifled barrels.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Typically BBs are used for indoor practice, casual outdoor plinking, training children, or to save money, as they are significantly cheaper than pellets.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Replica CO2 pistols allow people to train with a BB gun, saving a lot of money to centerfire firearm cartridges.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Care should be exercised to avoid ricochet, and safety glasses are recommended.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Recently, manufacturers have created frangible BBs, which break apart and do not ricochet, reducing the hazards associated with BB guns.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Some shotgunners use sightless BB rifles to train in instinctive shooting.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Similar guns were also used briefly by the United States Army in a Vietnam-era instinctive shooting program called "Quick Kill".
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] In the 18th and 19th centuries, air gun darts were popular, largely because they could be reused.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Although less popular now, several different types of darts are made to be used in air guns, but it is not recommended that darts be used in air guns with rifled bores or in spring-powered air guns.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Air guns that shoot darts are sometimes called *dart guns*, and *tranquilizer guns* if the darts used are loaded with anesthetic (tranquilizer) compounds.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Some modern air guns are designed to discharge arrows and are called *arrow guns* or sometimes *airbows*.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] These arrows are designed with a hollow shaft that is open in the rear where the nock would normally be.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] When loaded, the hollow arrow shaft is slid rearwards over a barrel whose external diameter is only fractionally smaller than the shaft's interior diameter, providing a close-enough fitting that minimizes rattling and gives a reasonable enveloping seal without causing too much friction.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] During shooting, the trigger releases high-pressure air from the barrel to the front portion of the hollow arrow shaft, pushing the arrow forward.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Such air guns can shoot arrows at launch velocities rivalling or even exceeding high-end crossbows, while retaining consistency of precision unaffected by archer's paradox, but they are also more expensive to set up and maintain.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The modern pentathlon has since 2009 included a laser-run event that replaced the traditional cross country run of 3,200 metres and timed air-pistol shoot.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The competitors run 4 laps of 800 m combined with 4 rounds of firing.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] The pistols used are modified air pistols that fire an eye-safe laser beam towards a target at the same time as a discharge of air.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] This has made the organisation of the events easier from a safety point of view and allows competitors to travel more easily with their weapons.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Airsoft pellets are plastic BBs shot from airsoft guns.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Larger caliber air rifles suitable for hunting large animals are offered by major manufacturers.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Custom air guns are available in even larger calibers such as 20 mm (0.79") or .87 (22.1 mm).
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] While in some countries air guns are not subject to any specific regulation, in most, there are laws which differ widely.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Each jurisdiction has its definition of an air gun.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Regulations may vary for weapons of different bore, muzzle energy, velocity, or ammunition material.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Guns designed to fire metal pellets are often more tightly controlled than airsoft weapons.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] There may be a minimum age for possession, and sales of both air guns and ammunition may be restricted.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] Some areas require permits and background checks similar to those required for propellant type firearms.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] While historical air guns have been made specifically for warfare, modern air guns can also be deadly.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] In medical literature, modern air guns have been noted as a cause of death.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] This has been the case for guns of caliber .177 and .22 that are within the legal muzzle energy of air guns in the United Kingdom.
[src:alligator-hunting/air-gun] For reason of safety and security a rule of use of the safety flag has been strictly mentioned by ISSF for the 10m air pistol and rifle shooting sports events.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama is nicknamed the *Yellowhammer State*, after the state bird.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama is also known as the "Heart of Dixie" and the "Cotton State".
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The state has diverse geography, with the north dominated by the mountainous Tennessee Valley and the south by Mobile Bay.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama's capital is Montgomery, and its largest city by population and area is Huntsville.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Its oldest city is Mobile, founded by French colonists (Alabama Creoles) in 1702 as the capital of French Louisiana.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Greater Birmingham is Alabama's largest metropolitan area and its economic center.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Politically, as part of the Deep South, or "Bible Belt", Alabama is a predominantly conservative state and is known for its Southern culture.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Within Alabama, American football, particularly at the college level, is part of the state's culture.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Originally the area of Alabama was home to many native tribes.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] It was a Spanish territory from the sixteenth century until the French acquired it in the early eighteenth century.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The British won the territory in 1763 until losing it in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Spain held Mobile as part of Spanish West Florida until 1813.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In December 1819, Alabama was recognized as a state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] During the antebellum period, Alabama was a major producer of cotton and widely used African American slave labor.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In 1861, the state seceded from the United States to become part of the Confederate States of America, with Montgomery acting as its first capital.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Following the American Civil War, it would suffer decades of economic hardship, in part due to agriculture and a few cash crops being the main driver of the state's economy.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Similar to other former slave states, Alabamian legislators employed Jim Crow laws from the late 19th century until the 1960s.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] High-profile events such as the Selma to Montgomery marches made the state a focal point of the civil rights movement in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] During and after World War II, the state's economy diversified with new industries.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In 1960, the establishment of NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville helped boost Alabama's economic growth by developing a local aerospace industry.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama's economy in the 21st century is based on automotive, finance, tourism, manufacturing, aerospace, mineral extraction, healthcare, education, retail, and technology.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Despite the economic and industrial growth in recent decades, Alabama typically ranks low in terms of health outcomes, educational attainment, and median household income.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The name of the Alabama River and state is derived from the Alabama people, a Muskogean-speaking tribe whose members lived just below the confluence of the Coosa and Tallapoosa rivers on the upper reaches of the river.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In the Alabama language, the word for a person of Alabama lineage is *Albaamo* (or variously *Albaama* or *Albàamo* in different dialects; the plural form is *Albaamaha*).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The word's spelling varies significantly among historical sources.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The first usage appears in three accounts of the Hernando de Soto expedition of 1540: Garcilaso de la Vega used *Alibamo*, while the Knight of Elvas and Rodrigo Ranjel wrote *Alibamu* and *Limamu*, respectively, in transliterations of the term.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] As early as 1702, the French called the tribe the *Alibamon*, with French maps identifying the river as *Rivière des Alibamons*.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Other spellings of the name have included *Alibamu*, *Alabamo*, *Albama*, *Alebamon*, *Alibama*, *Alibamou*, *Alabamu*, and *Allibamou*.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The use of state names derived from Native American languages is common in the U.S.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] An estimated 26 states have names of Native American origin.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Some scholars suggest the word comes from the Choctaw *alba* (meaning 'plants' or 'weeds') and *amo* (meaning 'to cut', 'to trim', or 'to gather').
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The meaning may have been 'clearers of the thicket' or 'herb gatherers', referring to clearing land for cultivation or collecting medicinal plants.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The state has numerous place names of Native American origin.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] An 1842 article in the *Jacksonville Republican* proposed it meant 'Here We Rest'.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] This notion was popularized in the 1850s through the writings of Alexander Beaufort Meek.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Experts in the Muskogean languages have not found any evidence to support such a translation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Indigenous peoples of varying cultures lived in the area for thousands of years before the advent of European colonization.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Trade with the northeastern tribes by the Ohio River began during the Burial Mound Period (1000 BC – 700 AD) and continued until European contact.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The agrarian Mississippian culture covered most of the state from 1000 to 1600 AD, with one of its major polities centered around what is now the Moundville Archaeological Site in Moundville, Alabama.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] This is the second-largest complex of the classic Middle Mississippian era, after Cahokia in present-day Illinois, which was the earliest center of the culture.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Analysis of artifacts from archaeological excavations at Moundville were the basis of scholars' formulating the characteristics of the Southeastern Ceremonial Complex (SECC).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Contrary to popular belief, the SECC appears to have no direct links to Mesoamerican culture but developed independently.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The Ceremonial Complex represents a major component of the religion of the Mississippian peoples; it is one of the primary means by which their religion is understood.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Among the historical tribes of Native American people living in present-day Alabama at the time of European contact were the Cherokee, an Iroquoian language people; and the Muskogean-speaking Alabama (*Alibamu*), Chickasaw, Choctaw, Creek, and Koasati.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] While part of the same large language family, the Muskogee tribes developed distinct cultures and languages.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The Spanish were the first Europeans to reach Alabama during their exploration of North America in the 16th century.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The expedition of Hernando de Soto passed through Mabila and other parts of the state in 1540.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] More than 160 years later, the French founded the region's first European settlement at Old Mobile in 1702.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The city was moved to the current site of Mobile in 1711.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] This area was claimed by the French from 1702 to 1763 as part of La Louisiane.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] After the French lost to the British in the Seven Years' War, it became part of British West Florida from 1763 to 1783.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] After the U.S. victory in the American Revolutionary War, the territory was divided between the United States and Spain.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The latter retained control of this western territory from 1783 until the surrender of the Spanish garrison at Mobile to U.S. forces on April 13, 1813.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Thomas Bassett, a loyalist to the British monarchy during the Revolutionary era, was one of the earliest white settlers in the state outside Mobile.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] He settled in the Tombigbee District during the early 1770s.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The district's boundaries were roughly limited to the area within a few miles of the Tombigbee River and included portions of what is today southern Clarke County, northernmost Mobile County, and most of Washington County.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] What are now Baldwin and Mobile counties became part of Spanish West Florida in 1783, part of the independent Republic of West Florida in 1810, and finally part of the Mississippi Territory in 1812.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Most of what is now the northern two-thirds of Alabama was known as the Yazoo lands beginning during the British colonial period.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] It was claimed by the Province of Georgia from 1767 onwards.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Following the American Revolutionary War, it remained a part of Georgia, although heavily disputed.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] With the exception of the area around Mobile and the Yazoo lands, what is now the lower one-third of Alabama was made part of the Mississippi Territory when it was organized in 1798.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The Yazoo lands were added to the territory in 1804, following the Yazoo land scandal.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Spain kept a claim on its former Spanish West Florida territory in what would become the coastal counties until the Adams–Onís Treaty officially ceded it to the U.S. in 1819.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The creation of the Mississippi Territory quickly prompted debates over its division.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Amid pressure from white southerners who sought the establishment of two slave states, Congress formed the Alabama Territory from the eastern half of the Mississippi Territory on March 3, 1817.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The legislation appointed William Wyatt Bibb of Georgia as the first governor of the newly designated Alabama Territory.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Before Mississippi's admission to statehood on December 10, 1817, the more sparsely settled eastern half of the territory was separated and named the Alabama Territory.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The United States Congress created the Alabama Territory on March 3, 1817.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Stephens, now abandoned, served as the territorial capital from 1817 to 1819.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama was admitted as the 22nd state on December 14, 1819, with Congress selecting Huntsville as the site for the first Constitutional Convention.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] From July 5 to August 2, 1819, delegates met to prepare the new state constitution.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Huntsville served as temporary capital from 1819 to 1820, when the seat of government moved to Cahaba in Dallas County.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Cahaba, now a ghost town, was the first permanent state capital from 1820 to 1825.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The Alabama Fever land rush was underway when the state was admitted to the Union, with settlers and land speculators pouring into the state to take advantage of fertile land suitable for cotton cultivation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Part of the frontier in the 1820s and 1830s, its constitution provided for universal suffrage for white men.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Southeastern planters and traders from the Upper South brought slaves with them as the cotton plantations in Alabama expanded.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The economy of the central Black Belt (named for its dark, productive soil) was built around large cotton plantations whose owners' wealth grew mainly from slave labor.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The area also drew many poor, disenfranchised people who became subsistence farmers.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama had an estimated population of under 10,000 people in 1810, but it increased to more than 300,000 people by 1830.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Most Native American tribes were completely removed from the state within a few years of the passage of the Indian Removal Act by Congress in 1830.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] From 1826 to 1846, Tuscaloosa served as Alabama's capital.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] On January 30, 1846, the Alabama legislature announced it had voted to move the capital city from Tuscaloosa to Montgomery.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The first legislative session in the new capital met in December 1847.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] A new capitol building was erected under the direction of Stephen Decatur Button of Philadelphia.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The first structure burned down in 1849, but was rebuilt on the same site in 1851.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] This second capitol building in Montgomery remains to the present day.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] It was designed by Barachias Holt of Exeter, Maine.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] By 1860, the population had increased to 964,201 people, of which nearly half, 435,080, were enslaved African Americans, and 2,690 were free people of color.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] On January 11, 1861, Alabama declared its secession from the Union.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] After remaining an independent republic for a few days, it joined the Confederate States of America.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The Confederacy's capital was initially at Montgomery.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama was heavily involved in the American Civil War.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Although comparatively few battles were fought in the state, Alabama contributed about 120,000 soldiers to the war effort.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] A company of cavalry soldiers from Huntsville, Alabama, joined Nathan Bedford Forrest's battalion in Hopkinsville, Kentucky.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The company wore new uniforms with yellow trim on the sleeves, collar and coattails.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] This led to them being greeted with "Yellowhammer", and the name later was applied to all Alabama troops in the Confederate Army.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama's slaves were freed by the 13th Amendment in 1865.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama was under military rule from the end of the war in May 1865 until its official restoration to the Union in 1868.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] From 1867 to 1874, with most white citizens barred temporarily from voting and freedmen enfranchised, many African Americans emerged as political leaders in the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama was represented in Congress during this period by three African-American congressmen: Jeremiah Haralson, Benjamin S.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Following the war, the state remained chiefly agricultural, with an economy tied to cotton.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] During the Reconstruction era, state legislators ratified a new state constitution in 1868 which created the state's first public school system and expanded women's rights.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Legislators funded numerous public road and railroad projects, although these were plagued with allegations of fraud and misappropriation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Organized insurgent, resistance groups tried to suppress the freedmen and Republicans.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] These groups included The Ku Klux Klan, the Pale Faces, Knights of the White Camellia, Red Shirts, and the White League.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Reconstruction in Alabama ended in 1874, when the Democrats regained control of the legislature and governor's office through an election dominated by fraud and violence.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] They wrote another constitution in 1875, and the legislature passed the Blaine Amendment, prohibiting public money from being used to finance religiously affiliated schools.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The same year, legislation was approved that called for racially segregated schools.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Railroad passenger cars were segregated in 1891.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The 1901 constitution required racial segregation of public schools.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] By 1903 only 2,980 African Americans were registered in Alabama, although at least 74,000 were literate.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] This compared to more than 181,000 African Americans eligible to vote in 1900.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The numbers dropped even more in later decades.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The state legislature passed additional racial segregation laws related to public facilities into the 1950s: jails were segregated in 1911; hospitals in 1915; toilets, hotels, and restaurants in 1928; and bus stop waiting rooms in 1945.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] While the planter class had persuaded poor whites to vote for this legislative effort to suppress black voting, the new restrictions resulted in their disenfranchisement as well, due mostly to the imposition of a cumulative poll tax.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] By 1941, whites constituted a slight majority of those disenfranchised by these laws: 600,000 whites vs.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Nearly all blacks had lost the ability to vote.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Despite numerous legal challenges which succeeded in overturning certain provisions, the state legislature would create new ones to maintain disenfranchisement.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The exclusion of blacks from the political system persisted until after passage of federal civil rights legislation in 1965 to enforce their constitutional rights as citizens.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The rural-dominated Alabama legislature consistently underfunded schools and services for the disenfranchised African Americans, but it did not relieve them of paying taxes.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Partially as a response to chronic underfunding of education for African Americans in the South, the Rosenwald Fund began funding the construction of what came to be known as Rosenwald Schools.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In Alabama, these schools were designed, and the construction partially financed with Rosenwald funds, which paid one-third of the construction costs.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The fund required the local community and state to raise matching funds to pay the rest.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Black residents effectively taxed themselves twice, by raising additional monies to supply matching funds for such schools, which were built in many rural areas.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] They often donated land and labor as well.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Beginning in 1913, the first 80 Rosenwald Schools were built in Alabama for African American children.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] A total of 387 schools, seven teachers' houses, and several vocational buildings were completed by 1937 in the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Several of the surviving school buildings in the state are now listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Reflecting this emigration, the population growth rate in Alabama (see "historical populations" table below) dropped by nearly half from 1910 to 1920.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] At the same time, many rural people migrated to the city of Birmingham to work in new industrial jobs.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Birmingham experienced such rapid growth it was called the "Magic City".
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] By 1920, Birmingham was the 36th-largest city in the United States.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Heavy industry and mining were the basis of its economy.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Its residents were under-represented for decades in the state legislature, which refused to redistrict after each decennial census according to population changes, as it was required by the state constitution.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] This did not change until the late 1960s following a lawsuit and court order.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Industrial development related to the demands of World War II brought a level of prosperity to the state not seen since before the civil war.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Rural workers poured into the largest cities in the state for better jobs and a higher standard of living.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] One example of this massive influx of workers occurred in Mobile.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Between 1940 and 1943, more than 89,000 people moved into the city to work for war-related industries.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Cotton and other cash crops faded in importance as the state developed a manufacturing and service base.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Despite massive population changes in the state from 1901 to 1961, the rural-dominated legislature refused to reapportion House and Senate seats based on population, as required by the state constitution to follow the results of decennial censuses.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] They held on to old representation to maintain political and economic power in agricultural areas.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] One result was that Jefferson County, containing Birmingham's industrial and economic powerhouse, contributed more than one-third of all tax revenue to the state, but did not receive a proportional amount in services.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Urban interests were consistently underrepresented in the legislature.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In the United States Supreme Court cases of *Baker v.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Sims* (1964), the court ruled that the principle of "one man, one vote" needed to be the basis of both houses of state legislatures, and that their districts had to be based on population rather than geographic counties.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] African Americans continued to press in the 1950s and 1960s to end disenfranchisement and segregation in the state through the civil rights movement, including legal challenges.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Board of Education* that public schools had to be desegregated, but Alabama was slow to comply.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] During the 1960s, under Governor George Wallace, Alabama resisted compliance with federal demands for desegregation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The civil rights movement had notable events in Alabama, including the Montgomery bus boycott (1955–1956), Freedom Rides in 1961, and 1965 Selma to Montgomery marches.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] These contributed to Congressional passage and enactment of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965 by the U.S.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Legal segregation ended in the states in 1964, although Jim Crow customs often continued until specifically challenged in court.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] According to *The New York Times*, by 2017, many of Alabama's African Americans were living in Alabama's cities such as Birmingham and Montgomery.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Also, the Black Belt region across central Alabama "is home to largely poor counties that are predominantly African-American.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In 1972, for the first time since 1901, the legislature completed the congressional redistricting based on the decennial census.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] This benefited the urban areas that had developed, as well as all in the population who had been underrepresented for more than sixty years.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Other changes were made to implement representative state house and senate districts.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama has made some changes since the late 20th century and has used new types of voting to increase representation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In the 1980s, an omnibus redistricting case, *Dillard v.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Crenshaw County*, challenged the at-large voting for representative seats of 180 Alabama jurisdictions, including counties and school boards.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] At-large voting had diluted the votes of any minority in a county, as the majority tended to take all seats.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Despite African Americans making up a significant minority in the state, they had been unable to elect any representatives in most of the at-large jurisdictions.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] As part of settlement of this case, five Alabama cities and counties, including Chilton County, adopted a system of cumulative voting for election of representatives in multi-seat jurisdictions.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] This has resulted in more proportional representation for voters.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In another form of proportional representation, 23 jurisdictions use limited voting, as in Conecuh County.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In 1982, limited voting was first tested in Conecuh County.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Together use of these systems has increased the number of African Americans and women being elected to local offices, resulting in governments that are more representative of their citizens.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Beginning in the 1960s, the state's economy shifted away from its traditional lumber, steel, and textile industries because of increased foreign competition.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] However, the state, particularly Huntsville, benefited from the opening of the George C.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Marshall Space Flight Center in 1960, a major facility in the development of the Saturn rocket program and the space shuttle.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Technology and manufacturing industries, such as automobile assembly, replaced some of the state's older industries in the late twentieth century, but the state's economy and growth lagged behind other states in the area, such as Georgia and Florida.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In 2001, Alabama Supreme Court chief justice Roy Moore installed a statue of the Ten Commandments in the capitol in Montgomery.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Circuit Court ordered the statue removed, but Moore refused to follow the court order, which led to protests around the capitol in favor of keeping the monument.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The monument was removed in August 2003.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] A few natural disasters have occurred in the state in the twenty-first century.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In 2004, Hurricane Ivan, a category 3 storm upon landfall, struck the state and caused over $18 billion of damage.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] It was among the most destructive storms to strike the state in its modern history.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] A super outbreak of 62 tornadoes hit the state in April 2011 and killed 238 people, devastating many communities.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama is the thirtieth-largest state in the United States with 52,419 square miles (135,760 km2) of total area: 3.2% of the area is water, making Alabama 23rd in the amount of surface water, also giving it the second-largest inland waterway system in the United States.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] About three-fifths of the land area is part of the Gulf Coastal Plain, a gentle plain with a general descent towards the Mississippi River and the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The North Alabama region is mostly mountainous, with the Tennessee River cutting a large valley and creating numerous creeks, streams, rivers, mountains, and lakes.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama is bordered by the states of Tennessee to the north, Georgia to the east, Florida to the south, and Mississippi to the west.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama has a coastline on the Gulf of Mexico, in the extreme southern edge of the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The state ranges in elevation from sea level at Mobile Bay to more than 2,000 feet (610 m) in the northeast, to Mount Cheaha at 2,413 ft (735 m).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama's land consists of 22 million acres (89,000 km2) of forest or 67% of the state's total land area.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Suburban Baldwin County, along the Gulf Coast, is the largest county in the state in both land area and water area.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Additionally, Alabama has four National Forests: Conecuh, Talladega, Tuskegee, and William B.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama also contains the Natchez Trace Parkway, the Selma To Montgomery National Historic Trail, and the Trail of Tears National Historic Trail.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] A 5-mile (8 km)-wide meteorite impact crater is located in Elmore County, just north of Montgomery.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] This is the Wetumpka crater, the site of "Alabama's greatest natural disaster".
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] A 1,000-foot (300 m)-wide meteorite hit the area about 80 million years ago.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In 2002, Christian Koeberl with the Institute of Geochemistry University of Vienna published evidence and established the site as the 157th recognized impact crater on Earth.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The state is classified as humid subtropical (*Cfa*) under the Köppen climate classification.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The average annual temperature is 64 °F (18 °C).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Temperatures tend to be warmer in the southern part of the state with its proximity to the Gulf of Mexico, while the northern parts of the state, especially in the Appalachian Mountains in the northeast, tend to be slightly cooler.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Generally, Alabama has very hot summers and mild winters with copious precipitation throughout the year.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama receives an average of 56 inches (1,400 mm) of rainfall annually and enjoys a lengthy growing season of up to 300 days in the southern part of the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Summers in Alabama are among the hottest in the U.S., with high temperatures averaging over 90 °F (32 °C) throughout the summer in some parts of the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama is also prone to tropical storms and hurricanes.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Areas of the state far away from the Gulf are not immune to the effects of the storms, which often dump tremendous amounts of rain as they move inland and weaken.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] South Alabama reports many thunderstorms.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The Gulf Coast, around Mobile Bay, averages between 70 and 80 days per year with thunder reported.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] This activity decreases somewhat further north in the state, but even the far north of the state reports thunder on about 60 days per year.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Occasionally, thunderstorms are severe with frequent lightning and large hail; the central and northern parts of the state are most vulnerable to this type of storm.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama ranks ninth in the number of deaths from lightning and tenth in the number of deaths from lightning strikes per capita.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama, along with Oklahoma and Iowa, has the most confirmed F5 and EF5 tornadoes of any state, according to statistics from the National Climatic Data Center for the period January 1, 1950, to June 2013.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Several long-tracked F5/EF5 tornadoes have contributed to Alabama reporting more tornado fatalities since 1950 than any other state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The state was affected by the 1974 Super Outbreak and was devastated tremendously by the 2011 Super Outbreak.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The 2011 Super Outbreak produced a record amount of tornadoes in the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The peak season for tornadoes varies from the northern to southern parts of the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama is one of the few places in the world that has a secondary tornado season in November and December besides the typically severe spring.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The northern part—along the Tennessee River Valley—is most vulnerable.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The area of Alabama and Mississippi most affected by tornadoes is sometimes referred to as Dixie Alley, as distinct from the Tornado Alley of the Southern Plains.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Winters are generally mild in Alabama, as they are throughout most of the Southeastern United States, with average January low temperatures around 40 °F (4 °C) in Mobile and around 32 °F (0 °C) in Birmingham.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Although snow is a rare event in much of Alabama, areas of the state north of Montgomery may receive a dusting of snow a few times every winter, with an occasional moderately heavy snowfall every few years.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Historic snowfall events include New Year's Eve 1963 snowstorm and the 1993 Storm of the Century.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The annual average snowfall for the Birmingham area is 2 inches (51 mm) per year.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In the southern Gulf coast, snowfall is less frequent, sometimes going several years without any snowfall.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama's highest temperature of 112 °F (44 °C) was recorded on September 5, 1925, in the unincorporated community of Centerville.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The record low of −27 °F (−33 °C) occurred on January 30, 1966, in New Market.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The state is usually ranked among the top in nation for its range of overall biodiversity.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama is in the subtropical coniferous forest biome and once boasted huge expanses of pine forest, which still form the largest proportion of forests in the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] It currently ranks fifth in the nation for the diversity of its flora.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] It is home to nearly 4,000 pteridophyte and spermatophyte plant species.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Indigenous animal species in the state include 62 mammal species, 93 reptile species, 73 amphibian species, roughly 307 native freshwater fish species, and 420 bird species that spend at least part of their year within the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Invertebrates include 97 crayfish species and 383 mollusk species.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] 113 of these mollusk species have never been collected outside the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] As of 2010, the state contains 461 municipalities, consisting of 174 cities and 287 towns.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Covering only 9.6% of Alabama's land mass, its municipalities are home to 60.4% of its population.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Montgomery, the state's capital, is the third-most populous settlement in Alabama; and the most populous city is Huntsville.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Census Bureau, the state contains 12 metropolitan statistical areas.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama's largest metropolitan area was Greater Birmingham.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] At the 1800 United States census, Alabama had a population of 1,250 people.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Since then, the state has continued to experience population growth with every U.S. census.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] According to the 2020 United States census the population of Alabama was 5,024,279, which represents an increase of 244,543 or 5.12%, since the 2010 census.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] This includes a natural increase since the last census of 121,054 (502,457 births minus 381,403 deaths) and an increase due to net migration of 104,991 into the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] According to statistics from 2012, immigration from outside the U.S. resulted in a net increase of 31,180 people, and migration within the country produced a net gain of 73,811 people.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The state had 108,000 foreign-born residents (2.4% of the state population), of which an estimated 22.2% were undocumented (24,000).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The top countries of origin for immigrants were Mexico, China, India, Germany and Guatemala as of 2018.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 3,752 homeless people in Alabama.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] With a population density of 99.2 people per square mile as of 2020, the majority of the state's population lives in North, Central, and South Alabama, spread throughout the Huntsville, Birmingham, Montgomery and Mobile metropolitan statistical areas.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The center of population of Alabama is located in Chilton County, outside the town of Jemison.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Many American Indian tribes such as the Cherokee, Chickasaw, Choctaw, and Coushatta inhabited present-day Alabama before European colonization.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] With Spanish, French, and British colonization of Alabama, white and black Americans migrated to the area.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] From European colonization to U.S. statehood, Alabama's population grew to become increasingly non-Hispanic white and African American.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] By the 2020 census, Alabama's total racial and ethnic population was 66.5% non-Hispanic white and 26.9% African American, with a growing Hispanic and Latino population of 5.3%.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabamians citing "American" ancestry are of overwhelmingly English extraction.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Demographers estimate that a minimum of 20–23% of people in Alabama are of predominantly English ancestry and state that the figure is probably much higher.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In the 1980 census, 1,139,976 people in Alabama cited that they were of English ancestry out of a total state population of 2,824,719 making them 41% of the state at the time and the largest ethnic group.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama has the 5th-highest black and African American population among U.S. states at 25.8% alone as of 2020.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In 2011, 46.6% of Alabama's population younger than age 1 were minorities.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The Scots-Irish were the largest non-English immigrant group from the British Isles before the American Revolution, and many settled in the South, later moving into the Deep South as it was developed.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In 1984, under the Davis–Strong Act, the state legislature established the Alabama Indian Affairs Commission.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Indigenous groups within the state had increasingly been demanding recognition as ethnic groups and seeking an end to discrimination.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Given the long history of slavery and associated racial segregation, the Native American or American Indian peoples, who have sometimes been of mixed race, have insisted on having their cultural identification respected.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In the past, their self-identification was often overlooked as the state tried to impose a binary breakdown of society into white and black.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The state has officially recognized nine American Indian tribes in the state, descended mostly from the Five Civilized Tribes of the American Southeast.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The state government has promoted recognition of American Indian contributions to the state, including the designation in 2000 for Columbus Day to be jointly celebrated as American Indian Heritage Day.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In 2020, 33,625 identified as being Native American alone, and 97,405 did in combination with one or more other races.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] According to the 2022 American Community Survey's estimates, approximately 94% of Alabamians speak English as their sole language, while 6% spoke a language other than English.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Of other languages, the majority of its multilingual population speaks Spanish (3.8%).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In a separate 2021 study by the American University Washington College of Law, Spanish was spoken by 156,656 residents.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Following, Korean, Vietnamese, Mandarin and Cantonese, German, French, and Tagalog were the most-spoken languages; among its French-speaking population, the majority have preserved their language since French colonization.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Pre-colonial and present-day Alabamians have adhered to multiple religions including Native American and African diaspora religions, and predominantly Christianity with the establishment of Spanish missions in Florida.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Other faiths including Judaism, Islam, and Indian religions were introduced since European colonization and American settlement.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] According to a 2023 Public Religion Research Institute survey, an estimated 80% of the adult population were Christian.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In the 2008 American Religious Identification Survey, 86% of Alabama respondents reported their religion as Christian, including 6% Catholic, with 11% as having no religion.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The composition of other traditions is 0.5% Mormon, 0.5% Jewish, 0.5% Muslim, 0.5% Buddhist, and 0.5% Hindu.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama is located in the middle of the Bible Belt, a region of numerous Protestant Christians.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama has been identified as one of the most religious states in the United States, with about 58% of the population attending church regularly.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] A majority of people in the state identify as Evangelical Protestant.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] As of 2010, the three largest denominational groups in Alabama are the Southern Baptist Convention, The United Methodist Church, and non-denominational Evangelical Protestant.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In Alabama, the Southern Baptist Convention has the highest number of adherents with 1,380,121; this is followed by the United Methodist Church with 327,734 adherents, non-denominational Evangelical Protestant with 220,938 adherents, and the Catholic Church with 150,647 adherents.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Many Baptist and Methodist congregations became established in the Great Awakening of the early 19th century, when preachers proselytized across the South.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The Assemblies of God had almost 60,000 members, the Churches of Christ had nearly 120,000 members.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In a 2007 survey, nearly 70% of respondents could name all four of the Christian Gospels.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Of those who indicated a religious preference, 59% said they possessed a "full understanding" of their faith and needed no further learning.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In a 2007 poll, 92% of Alabamians reported having at least some confidence in churches in the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Although in much smaller numbers, many other religious faiths are represented in the state as well, including Judaism, Islam, Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism, the Baháʼí Faith, and Unitarian Universalism.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Jews have been present in what is now Alabama since 1763, during the colonial era of Mobile, when Sephardic Jews immigrated from London.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The oldest Jewish congregation in the state is Congregation Sha'arai Shomayim in Mobile.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] It was formally recognized by the state legislature on January 25, 1844.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Later immigrants in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries tended to be Ashkenazi Jews from eastern Europe.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Jewish denominations in the state include two Orthodox, four Conservative, ten Reform, and one Humanistic synagogue.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Muslims have been increasing in Alabama, with 31 mosques built by 2011, many by African-American converts.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] There are six Dharma centers and organizations for Theravada Buddhists.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Most monastic Buddhist temples are concentrated in southern Mobile County, near Bayou La Batre.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] This area has attracted an influx of refugees from Cambodia, Laos, and Vietnam during the 1970s and thereafter.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The four temples within a ten-mile radius of Bayou La Batre, include Chua Chanh Giac, Wat Buddharaksa, and Wat Lao Phoutthavihan.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] The first community of adherents of the Baháʼí Faith in Alabama was founded in 1896 by Paul K.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Dealy, who moved from Chicago to Fairhope.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Baháʼí centers in Alabama exist in Birmingham, Huntsville, and Florence.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] In 2018, life expectancy in Alabama was 75.1 years, below the national average of 78.7 years and is the third lowest life expectancy in the country.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Factors that can cause lower life expectancy are maternal mortality, suicide, and gun crimes.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] A Centers for Disease Control and Prevention study in 2008 showed that obesity in Alabama is a problem, with most counties having more than 29% of adults obese, except for ten which had a rate between 26% and 29%.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Residents of the state, along with those in five other states, were least likely in the nation to be physically active during leisure time.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p01] Alabama, and the southeastern U.S. in general, has one of the highest incidences of adult onset diabetes in the country, exceeding 10% of adults.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Bureau of Economic Analysis, in 2025, Alabama's total gross state product was $341.1 billion, and the state's per capita personal income was $59,677.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The state has invested in aerospace, education, health care, banking, and various heavy industries, including automobile manufacturing, mineral extraction, steel production and fabrication.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] By 2006, crop and animal production in Alabama was valued at $1.5 billion.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In contrast to the primarily agricultural economy of the previous century, this was only about one percent of the state's gross domestic product.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The number of private farms has declined at a steady rate since the 1960s, as land has been sold to developers, timber companies, and large farming conglomerates.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In 2025, 99.4% of Alabama businesses were small businesses and employed 46.0% of the state's workforce.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The state's seasonally adjusted unemployment rate was 5.8% in April 2015.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] This compared to a nationwide seasonally adjusted rate of 5.4%.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] As of May 2025, the unemployment rate was 3.3%.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama has no minimum wage and in February 2016 passed legislation preventing municipalities from setting one.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] As of 2018, Alabama has the sixth highest poverty rate among states in the U.S.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In 2017, United Nations Special Rapporteur Philip Alston toured parts of rural Alabama and observed environmental conditions that he said were poorer than anywhere he had seen in the developed world.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama's agricultural outputs include poultry and eggs, cattle, fish, plant nursery items, peanuts, cotton, grains such as corn and sorghum, vegetables, milk, soybeans, and peaches.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Although known as "The Cotton State", Alabama ranks between eighth and tenth in national cotton production, according to various reports, with Texas, Georgia and Mississippi comprising the top three.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Aquaculture is a large part of the economy of Alabama.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabamians began to practice aquaculture in the early 1960s.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] U.S. farm-raised catfish is the 8th most popular seafood product in America.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] By 2008, approximately 4,000 people in Alabama were employed by the catfish industry and Alabama produced 132 million pounds of catfish.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In 2020, Alabama produced 1⁄3 of the United States' farm-raised catfish.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The total 2020 sales of catfish raised in Alabama equaled $307 million but by 2020 the total employment of Alabamians fell to 2,442.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] From the early 2000s to 2020, the Alabamian catfish industry has declined from 250 farms and 4 processors to 66 farms and 2 processors.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Reasons for this decline include increased feed prices, catfish alternatives, COVID-19's impact on restaurant sales, disease, and fish size.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama's industrial outputs include iron and steel products (including cast-iron and steel pipe); paper, lumber, and wood products; mining (mostly coal); plastic products; cars and trucks; and apparel.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In addition, Alabama produces aerospace and electronic products, mostly in the Huntsville area, the location of NASA's George C.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Marshall Space Flight Center and the U.S.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Army Materiel Command, headquartered at Redstone Arsenal.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] A great deal of Alabama's economic growth since the 1990s has been due to the state's expanding automotive manufacturing industry.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Located in the state are Honda Manufacturing of Alabama, Hyundai Motor Manufacturing Alabama, Mercedes-Benz U.S.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] International, and Toyota Motor Manufacturing Alabama, as well as their various suppliers.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Since 1993, the automobile industry has generated more than 67,800 new jobs in the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama currently ranks 4th in the nation for vehicle exports.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Automakers accounted for approximately a third of the industrial expansion in the state in 2012.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The eight models produced at the state's auto factories totaled combined sales of 74,335 vehicles for 2012.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The strongest model sales during this period were the Hyundai Elantra compact car, the Mercedes-Benz GL-Class sport utility vehicle and the Honda Ridgeline sport utility truck.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Steel producers Outokumpu, Nucor, SSAB, ThyssenKrupp, and U.S.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Steel have facilities in Alabama and employ more than 10,000 people.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In May 2007, German steelmaker ThyssenKrupp selected Calvert in Mobile County for a 4.65 billion combined stainless and carbon steel processing facility.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] ThyssenKrupp's stainless steel division, Inoxum, including the stainless portion of the Calvert plant, was sold to Finnish stainless steel company Outokumpu in 2012.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The remaining portion of the ThyssenKrupp plant had final bids submitted by ArcelorMittal and Nippon Steel for $1.6 billion in March 2013.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Companhia Siderúrgica Nacional submitted a combined bid for the mill at Calvert, plus a majority stake in the ThyssenKrupp mill in Brazil, for $3.8 billion.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In July 2013, the plant was sold to ArcelorMittal and Nippon Steel.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The Hunt Refining Company, a subsidiary of Hunt Consolidated, Inc., is based in Tuscaloosa and operates a refinery there.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The company also operates terminals in Mobile, Melvin, and Moundville.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] JVC America, Inc. operates an optical disc replication and packaging plant in Tuscaloosa.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company operates a large plant in Gadsden which employs about 1,400 people.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Construction of an Airbus A320 family aircraft assembly plant in Mobile was formally announced by Airbus CEO Fabrice Brégier from the Mobile Convention Center on July 2, 2012.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The plans include a $600 million factory at the Brookley Aeroplex for the assembly of the A319, A320 and A321 aircraft.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Construction began in 2013, with plans for it to become operable by 2015 and produce up to 50 aircraft per year by 2017.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The assembly plant is the company's first factory to be built within the United States.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] It was announced on February 1, 2013, that Airbus had hired Alabama-based Hoar Construction to oversee construction of the facility.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The factory officially opened on September 14, 2015, covering one million square feet on 53 acres of flat grassland.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] According to Business Insider, Alabama ranked 14th in most popular states to visit in 2014.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] An estimated 26 million tourists visited the state in 2017 and spent $14.3 billion, providing directly or indirectly 186,900 jobs in the state, which includes 362,000 International tourists spending $589 million.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Mobile is known for having the oldest organized Mardi Gras celebration in the United States, beginning in 1703.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] It was also host to the first formally organized Mardi Gras parade in the U.S. in 1830, a tradition that continues to this day.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Mardi Gras is an official state holiday in Mobile and Baldwin counties.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In 2018, Mobile's Mardi Gras parade was the state's top event, producing the most tourists with an attendance of 892,811.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Space & Rocket Center in Huntsville with an attendance of 849,981, followed by the Birmingham Zoo with 543,090.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Of the parks and natural destinations, Alabama's Gulf Coast topped the list with 6,700,000 visitors.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama has historically been a popular region for film shoots due to its diverse landscapes and contrast of environments.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Movies filmed in Alabama include *Close Encounters of the Third Kind*, *Get Out*, *42*, *Selma*, *Big Fish*, *The Final Destination*, *Due Date*, and *Need for Speed*.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] UAB Hospital, USA Health University Hospital, Huntsville Hospital, and Children's Hospital of Alabama are the only Level I trauma centers in Alabama.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] UAB is the largest state government employer in Alabama, with a workforce of about 18,000.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] A 2017 study found that Alabama had the least competitive health insurance market in the country, with Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Alabama having a market share of 84% followed by UnitedHealth Group at 7%.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Regions Financial Corporation is the largest bank headquartered in or operating in Alabama.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] PNC Financial Services and Wells Fargo also have a major presence in Alabama.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Wells Fargo has a regional headquarters, an operations center campus, and a $400 million data center in Birmingham.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Many smaller banks are also headquartered in the Birmingham area, including ServisFirst and New South Federal Savings Bank.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Birmingham also serves as the headquarters for several large investment management companies, including Harbert Management Corporation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Telecommunications provider AT&T, formerly BellSouth, has a major presence in Alabama with several large offices in Birmingham.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Many technology companies are headquartered in Huntsville, such as ADTRAN, a network access company; Intergraph, a computer graphics company; and Avocent, an IT infrastructure company.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Brasfield & Gorrie, BE&K, Hoar Construction, and B.L.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Harbert International, based in Alabama and subsidiaries of URS Corporation, are all routinely are included in the Engineering News-Record lists of top design, international construction, and engineering firms.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The foundational document for Alabama's government is the Alabama Constitution, the current constitution was adopted in 2022.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The former Alabama constitution adopted in 1901 was, with over 850 amendments and almost 87,000 words, by some accounts the world's longest constitution and roughly forty times the length of the United States Constitution.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] There was a significant movement to rewrite and modernize Alabama's constitution.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The former constitution was particularly criticized for its complexity and length intentionally codifying segregation and racism.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama's government is divided into three coequal branches.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The legislative branch is the Alabama Legislature, a bicameral assembly composed of the Alabama House of Representatives, with 105 members, and the Alabama Senate, with 35 members.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The Legislature is responsible for writing, debating, passing, or defeating state legislation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The Republican Party currently holds a majority in both houses of the Legislature.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The Legislature has the power to override a gubernatorial veto by a simple majority (most state Legislatures require a two-thirds majority to override a veto).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Until 1964, the state elected state senators on a geographic basis by county, with one per county.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] It had not redistricted congressional districts since passage of its constitution in 1901; as a result, urbanized areas were grossly underrepresented.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] It had not changed legislative districts to reflect the decennial censuses, either.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] At that time, Alabama and many other states had to change their legislative districting, as many across the country had systems that underrepresented urban areas and districts.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] This had caused decades of underinvestment in such areas.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] For instance, Birmingham and Jefferson County taxes had supplied one-third of the state budget, but Jefferson County received only 1/67th of state services in funding.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Through the legislative delegations, the Alabama legislature kept control of county governments.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The executive branch is responsible for the execution and oversight of laws.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] It is headed by the governor of Alabama.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Other members of the executive branch include the cabinet, the lieutenant governor of Alabama, the Attorney General of Alabama, the Alabama Secretary of State, the Alabama State Treasurer, and the State Auditor of Alabama.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The current governor is Republican Kay Ivey.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The members of the Legislature take office immediately after the November elections.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Statewide officials, such as the governor, lieutenant governor, attorney general, and other constitutional officers, take office the following January.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The judiciary is responsible for interpreting the Constitution of Alabama and applying the law in state criminal and civil cases.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The state's highest court is the Supreme Court of Alabama.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama uses partisan elections to select judges.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Since the 1980s judicial campaigns have become increasingly politicized.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The current chief justice of the Alabama Supreme Court is Republican Tom Parker.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] All sitting justices on the Alabama Supreme Court are members of the Republican Party.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] There are two intermediate appellate courts, the Court of Civil Appeals and the Court of Criminal Appeals, and four trial courts: the circuit court (trial court of general jurisdiction), and the district, probate, and municipal courts.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama has the death penalty with authorized methods of execution that include the electric chair and the gas chamber.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Some critics believe the election of judges has contributed to an exceedingly high rate of executions.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama has the highest per capita death penalty rate in the country.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In some years, it imposes more death sentences than does Texas, a state which has a population five times larger.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] However, executions per capita are significantly higher in Texas.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Some of its cases have been highly controversial; the U.S.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Supreme Court has overturned 83 convictions in death penalty cases.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] It was the only state to allow judges to override jury decisions in whether or not to use a death sentence; in 10 cases judges overturned sentences of life imprisonment without parole that were voted unanimously by juries.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] This judicial authority was removed in April 2017.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] On May 14, 2019, Alabama passed the Human Life Protection Act, banning abortion at any stage of pregnancy unless there is a "serious health risk", with no exceptions for rape and incest.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The law subjects doctors who perform abortions with 10 to 99 years imprisonment.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The law was originally supposed to take effect the following November, but on October 29, 2019, U.S.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] District Judge Myron Thompson blocked the law from taking effect due to it being in conflict with the 1973 U.S.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, Judge Thompson lifted the injunction, allowing the law to go into effect.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama is one of five to not operate a state lottery and one of just two states, the other being Utah, that prohibits the creation of state lotteries in their constitutions.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Taxes are collected by the Alabama Department of Revenue.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama levies a 2%, 4%, or 5% personal income tax, depending on the amount earned and filing status.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Taxpayers are allowed to deduct their federal income tax from their Alabama state tax, even if taking the standard deduction; those who itemize can also deduct FICA (the Social Security and Medicare tax).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The state's general sales tax rate is 4%.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Sales tax rates for cities and counties are also added to purchases.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] For example, the total sales tax rate in Mobile County is 10% and there is an additional restaurant tax of 1%, which means a diner in Mobile County would pay an 11% tax on a meal.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In 2020, sales and excise taxes in Alabama accounted for 38% of all state and local revenue.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama gradually reduced the grocery tax to 2% between 2024 and 2025.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In April 2026, Alabama paused the grocery tax for the months of May and July of that year.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The corporate income tax rate in Alabama is 6.5%.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The overall federal, state, and local tax burden in Alabama ranks the state as the second least tax-burdened state in the country.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Property taxes of 0.40% of assessed value per year, are the second-lowest in the U.S., after Hawaii.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The state constitution currently requires a voter referendum to raise property taxes.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Historically, an Alabama excise tax "on the storage, use or other consumption in this state of tangible personal property purchased at retail for storage, use or other consumption in this state" was the focus of a 1941 U S Supreme Court ruling, *Curry v United States*.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Each county has its own elected legislative branch, usually called the county commission.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] It also has limited executive authority in the county.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Because of the constraints of the Alabama Constitution, which centralizes power in the state legislature, only seven counties (Jefferson, Lee, Mobile, Madison, Montgomery, Shelby, and Tuscaloosa) in the state have limited home rule.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Instead, most counties in the state must lobby the Local Legislation Committee of the state legislature to get simple local policies approved, ranging from waste disposal to land use zoning.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The state legislature has retained power over local governments by refusing to pass a constitutional amendment establishing home rule for counties, as recommended by the 1973 Alabama Constitutional Commission.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Legislative delegations retain certain powers over each county.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] United States Supreme Court decisions in *Baker v.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Carr* (1964) required that both houses have districts established on the basis of population, and redistricted after each census, to implement the principle of "one man, one vote".
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Before that, each county was represented by one state senator, leading to under-representation in the state senate for more urbanized, populous counties.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The rural bias of the state legislature, which had also failed to redistrict seats in the state house, affected politics well into the 20th century, failing to recognize the rise of industrial cities and urbanized areas.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] "The lack of home rule for counties in Alabama has resulted in the proliferation of local legislation permitting counties to do things not authorized by the state constitution.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama's constitution has been amended more than 700 times, and almost one-third of the amendments are local in nature, applying to only one county or city.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama is an alcoholic beverage control state, meaning the state government holds a monopoly on the sale of alcohol.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The Alabama Alcoholic Beverage Control Board controls the sale and distribution of alcoholic beverages in the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] A total of 25 of the 67 counties are "dry counties" which ban the sale of alcohol, and there are many dry municipalities in counties which permit alcohol sales.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] During Reconstruction following the American Civil War, Alabama was occupied by federal troops of the Third Military District under General John Pope.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In 1874, the political coalition of white Democrats known as the Redeemers took control of the state government from the Republicans, in part by suppressing the black vote through violence, fraud, and intimidation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] After 1890, a coalition of White Democratic politicians passed laws to segregate and disenfranchise African American residents, a process completed in provisions of the 1901 constitution.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Provisions which disenfranchised blacks resulted in excluding many poor Whites.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] By 1941 more Whites than Blacks had been disenfranchised: 600,000 to 520,000.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The total effects were greater on the black community, as almost all its citizens were disfranchised and relegated to separate and unequal treatment under the law.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] From 1901 through the 1960s, the state did not redraw election districts as population grew and shifted within the state during urbanization and industrialization of certain areas.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] As counties were the basis of election districts, the result was a rural minority that dominated state politics through nearly three-quarters of the century, until a series of federal court cases required redistricting in 1972 to meet equal representation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama state politics gained nationwide and international attention in the 1950s and 1960s during the civil rights movement, when whites bureaucratically, and at times violently, resisted protests for electoral and social reform.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Governor George Wallace, the state's only four-term governor, was a controversial figure who vowed to maintain segregation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Only after passage of the federal Civil Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965 did African Americans regain the ability to exercise suffrage, among other civil rights.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In many jurisdictions, they continued to be excluded from representation by at-large electoral systems, which allowed the majority of the population to dominate elections.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Some changes at the county level have occurred following court challenges to establish single-member districts that enable a more diverse representation among county boards.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In 2007, the Alabama Legislature passed, and Republican governor Bob Riley signed a resolution expressing "profound regret" over slavery and its lingering impact.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In a symbolic ceremony, the bill was signed in the Alabama State Capitol, which housed Congress of the Confederate States of America.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In 2010, Republicans won control of both houses of the legislature for the first time in 136 years.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] As of February 2023, there are a total of 3,707,233 registered voters, with 3,318,679 active, and the others inactive in the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The 2023 *American Values Atlas* by Public Religion Research Institute found that a majority of Alabama residents support same-sex marriage.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] With the disfranchisement of Blacks in 1901, the state became part of the "Solid South", a system in which the Democratic Party operated as effectively the only viable political party in every Southern state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] For nearly a hundred years local and state elections in Alabama were decided in the Democratic Party primary, with generally only token Republican challengers running in the general election.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Since the mid- to late 20th century, however, white conservatives started shifting to the Republican Party.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In Alabama, majority-white districts are now expected to regularly elect Republican candidates to federal, state and local office.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Members of the nine seats on the Supreme Court of Alabama and all ten seats on the state appellate courts are elected to office.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Until 1994, no Republicans held any of the court seats.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In that general election, the then-incumbent chief justice, Ernest C.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Hornsby, refused to leave office after losing the election by approximately 3,000 votes to Republican Perry O.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Hornsby sued Alabama and defiantly remained in office for nearly a year before finally giving up the seat after losing in court.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The Democrats lost the last of the nineteen court seats in August 2011 with the resignation of the last Democrat on the bench.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In the early 21st century, Republicans hold all seven of the statewide elected executive branch offices.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Republicans hold six of the eight elected seats on the Alabama State Board of Education.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In 2010, Republicans took large majorities of both chambers of the state legislature, giving them control of that body for the first time in 136 years.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The last remaining statewide Democrat, who served on the Alabama Public Service Commission, was defeated in 2012.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Only three Republican lieutenant governors have been elected since the end of Reconstruction, when Republicans generally represented Reconstruction government, including the newly emancipated freedmen who had gained the franchise.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The three GOP lieutenant governors are Steve Windom (1999–2003), Kay Ivey (2011–2017), and Will Ainsworth (2019–present).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Many metropolitan and suburban counties have voters who are majority Democrats, resulting in local elections being decided in the Democratic primary.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Similarly, most rural counties are majority-Republican and elections are effectively decided in the Republican primary.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] However, since local governments in Alabama are weaker than in other parts of the country, Republicans have the upper hand in government.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama's 67 county sheriffs are elected in partisan, at-large races, and Republicans retain the vast majority of those posts.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The current split is 18 Democrats, and 49 Republicans as of 2023.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] However, most of the Democratic sheriffs preside over urban and more populated counties.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The majority of Republican sheriffs have been elected in the more rural counties with lower population.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] As of 2025, the state of Alabama has 11 African-American sheriffs.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The state's two U.S. senators are Katie Britt and Tommy Tuberville, both of whom are Republican.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] House of Representatives, the state is represented by seven members, five of whom are Republicans (Mike Rogers, Robert Aderholt, Dale Strong, Barry Moore, and Gary Palmer) and two Democrats (Terri Sewell and Shomari Figures).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Public primary and secondary education in Alabama is under the purview of the Alabama State Board of Education as well as local oversight by 67 county school boards and 60 city boards of education.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Together, 1,496 individual schools provide education for 744,637 elementary and secondary students.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Public school funding is appropriated through the Alabama Legislature through the Education Trust Fund.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] That represented an increase of $444,736,387 over the previous fiscal year.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In 2007, more than 82 percent of schools made Adequate Yearly Progress (AYP) toward student proficiency under the National No Child Left Behind law, using measures determined by the state of Alabama.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] While Alabama's public education system has improved in recent decades, it lags behind in achievement compared to other states.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Census data (2000), Alabama's high school graduation rate (75%) is the fourth lowest in the U.S.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] (after Kentucky, Louisiana and Mississippi).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The largest educational gains were among people with some college education but without degrees.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] According to National Assessment of Educational Progress (NEAP), Alabama ranks 39 in reading and 40 in math among fourth-grade students in the rankings from 2022.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Generally prohibited in the West at large, school corporal punishment is not unusual in Alabama, with 27,260 public school students paddled at least one time, according to government data for the 2011–2012 school year.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The rate of school corporal punishment in Alabama is surpassed by only Mississippi and Arkansas.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama's programs of higher education include 14 four-year public universities, two-year community colleges, and 17 private, undergraduate and graduate universities.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Public, post-secondary education in Alabama is overseen by the Alabama Commission on Higher Education and the Alabama Department of Postsecondary Education.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Colleges and universities in Alabama offer degree programs from two-year associate degrees to a multitude of doctoral level programs.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The largest single campus in Alabama is Tuskegee University with 5000 acres.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The largest student body is the University of Alabama, located in Tuscaloosa, with 42,360 students enrolled for fall 2025.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Troy University was the largest institution in the state in 2010, with an enrollment of 29,689 students across four Alabama campuses (Troy, Dothan, Montgomery, and Phenix City), as well as sixty learning sites in seventeen other states and eleven other countries.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The oldest institutions are the public University of North Alabama in Florence and the Catholic Church-affiliated Spring Hill College in Mobile, both founded in 1830.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] News & World Report*, Alabama had three universities ranked in the top 100 Public Schools in America (Auburn University at 47, University of Alabama at Birmingham (UAB) at 76, and University of Alabama at 91).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] News & World Report*, Alabama had four tier one universities (Auburn University, University of Alabama at Birmingham (UAB), University of Alabama and University of Alabama in Huntsville).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Major newspapers include *Birmingham News*, Mobile *Press-Register*, and *Montgomery Advertiser*.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama literature is characterized by themes of race and issues of gender and war, and is influenced by events such as the American Civil War, the Reconstruction era, the civil rights movement, and the Vietnam War.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Some notable examples of Alabama literature include Harper Lee's *To Kill a Mockingbird*, Winston Groom's *Forrest Gump*, Fannie Flagg's *Fried Green Tomatoes at the Whistle Stop Cafe*, and the biographies of Rosa Parks and Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama has several professional and semi-professional sports teams, including three minor league baseball teams.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The Talladega Superspeedway motorsports complex hosts a series of NASCAR events.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] It has a seating capacity of 143,000 and is the thirteenth largest stadium in the world and sixth largest stadium in America.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Also, the Barber Motorsports Park has hosted IndyCar Series and Rolex Sports Car Series races.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The ATP Birmingham was a World Championship Tennis tournament held from 1973 to 1980.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama has hosted several professional golf tournaments, such as the 1984 and 1990 PGA Championship at Shoal Creek, the Barbasol Championship (PGA Tour), the Mobile LPGA Tournament of Champions, Airbus LPGA Classic, and Yokohama Tire LPGA Classic (LPGA Tour), and The Tradition (Champions Tour).
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] College football is extremely popular in Alabama, particularly the University of Alabama Crimson Tide and Auburn University Tigers, rivals in the Southeastern Conference.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Alabama averages over 100,000 fans per game and Auburn averages over 80,000—both numbers among the top twenty in the nation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Bryant–Denny Stadium is the home of the Alabama football team, and has a seating capacity of 101,821, and is the fifth largest stadium in America.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Jordan-Hare Stadium is the home field of the Auburn football team and seats up to 87,451.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Protective Stadium is home of the UAB Blazers football program and the Birmingham Bowl.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Opening in 2020, Hancock Whitney Stadium in Mobile is the home of the University of South Alabama football team, and serves as the home of the Reese's Senior Bowl, the AHSAA North/South All-star Game, and the LendingTree Bowl; the stadium seats 25,450.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In 2009, Bryant–Denny Stadium and Jordan-Hare Stadium became the homes of the Alabama High School Athletic Association state football championship games, after previously being held at Legion Field in Birmingham.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] For rail transport, Amtrak schedules the *Crescent*, a daily passenger train, running from New York to New Orleans with station stops at Anniston, Birmingham, and Tuscaloosa.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The *Mardi Gras Service* operates daily between Mobile and New Orleans; the Mobile terminus is its only Alabama stop.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] I-22 enters the state from Mississippi and connects Birmingham with Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] In addition, there are currently five auxiliary interstate routes in the state: I-165 in Mobile, I-359 in Tuscaloosa, I-459 around Birmingham, I-565 in Decatur and Huntsville, and I-759 in Gadsden.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] A sixth route, I-685, will be formed when I-85 is rerouted along a new southern bypass of Montgomery.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] A proposed northern bypass of Birmingham will be designated as I-422.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Since a direct connection from I-22 to I-422 will not be possible, I-222 has been proposed, as well.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] Highways also pass through the state, such as U.S.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] There are four toll roads in the state: Montgomery Expressway in Montgomery; Northport/Tuscaloosa Western Bypass in Tuscaloosa and Northport; Emerald Mountain Expressway in Wetumpka; and Beach Express in Orange Beach.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The Port of Mobile, Alabama's only saltwater port, is a large seaport on the Gulf of Mexico with inland waterway access to the Midwest by way of the Tennessee–Tombigbee Waterway.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The Port of Mobile was ranked 12th by tons of traffic in the United States during 2009.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The newly expanded container terminal at the Port of Mobile was ranked as the 25th busiest for container traffic in the nation during 2011.
[src:alligator-hunting/alabama-p02] The state's other ports are on rivers with access to the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] A **crocodile farm** or **alligator farm** is an establishment for breeding and raising of crocodilians in order to produce crocodile and alligator meat, leather from crocodile and alligator skin, and other goods.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Many species of both alligators and crocodiles are farmed internationally.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] In Louisiana alone, alligator farming is a $60 to $70 million industry.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Most crocodile farms are located in Thailand.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Around 1.33-1.5 million crocodiles were slaughtered from 2007 to 2010 in crocodile farms.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Alligators and crocodiles are not truly domesticated and their being bred in farms probably began as late as the early 20th century.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Most of the early businesses, such as St.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Augustine Alligator Farm Zoological Park, established in 1893, were farms in name only, primarily keeping alligators and crocodiles as a tourist attraction.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Only in the 1960s did commercial operations that either harvested eggs from the wild or bred alligators on-site begin to appear.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] This was largely driven by diminishing stocks of wild alligators, which had been hunted nearly to extinction by that time.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] As the American alligator was placed under official protection in 1967 (under a law preceding the 1973 Endangered Species Act), farming alligators for skins became the most viable option for producing leather.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Mostly concentrated in the Southern U.S. states of Louisiana, Florida, and Georgia, the practice quickly spread to other nations.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Both the American and Chinese alligator are farmed intensively today, mostly within each species' respective native region.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] The Nile crocodile is found in ranches all over Africa, and the saltwater crocodile is farmed in Australia and other areas.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] The smaller caimans are generally not of enough market value to farm, though captive breeding of the spectacled caiman does take place in South America.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Farming alligators and crocodiles first grew out of the demand for skins, which can fetch hundreds of dollars each.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] But alligator and crocodile meat, long a part of Southern cooking (especially Cajun cuisine) and some Asian and African cuisines, began to be sold and shipped to markets unfamiliar with crocodilian meat.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Chinese cuisine based on traditional Chinese medicine considers the meat to be a curative food for colds and cancer prevention, although there is no scientific evidence to support this.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Crocodile meat was eaten, albeit rarely and as an exotic dish, in Vietnamese cuisine, but it was taboo and off limits for Chinese.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] In Vietnam, skinning is performed on still living crocodiles.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] A common misconception is that crocodilians are an easy source of revenue and not difficult to care for in captivity; however, few crocodilian businesses are successful in the developing world.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] To offset overhead costs and have a regular source of income, crocodilian facilities can add tourism; in this way alligator farming can assist native species and provide people with work.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Alligator farming has minimal adverse effects on the environment, and has at least two positive direct effects on alligator conservation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Because the luxury goods industry has a reliable stream of product, illegal poaching is reduced.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Juvenile crocodilians can also be released into the wild to support a steady population.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Wild alligator conservation has also benefited indirectly from farming.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Ranching businesses protect alligator habitats to take care of nesting sites.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] The fiscal incentive to keep a healthy environment for breeding alligators means that the environment and its wildlife are seen as an economic resource.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] This can augment the government's willingness to take care of crocodilian populations.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Animals other than crocodilians may benefit from a similar application of sustainable and ethical farming.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Ranching, wild harvesting, and captive breeding are the three ways to obtain crocodilians recognized by the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) and the Crocodile Specialist Group (CSG).
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Alligators can be raised in captivity on farms or on ranches.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Alligator farms breed alligators, whereas ranches incubate and rear hatchlings collected from the wild.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Farms do collect eggs from the wild but they also keep breeding adults in their facilities to produce their own eggs whereas ranches do not.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Farming and ranching operations typically return a certain percentage of juveniles to the wild at a size associated with a high survival rate, an approach that increases overall alligator survival rates from the low numbers of successful eggs and juveniles usually observed in the wild.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Crocodiles can be housed in a number of ways depending on the goals of the rearing facility.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Large areas of a lake or marsh can be enclosed for many individuals or a smaller area can be created for fewer individuals.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Due to the size and lifespan of the animals, adult crocodiles need a substantial amount of space.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Tourism can bring additional revenue to crocodile rearing facilities, but they must be made safe for the public and the crocodiles, while maintaining an aesthetically pleasing environment.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] This frequently depends on enclosures that can be easily cleaned without harming the animals.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] If closed to public viewing, facilities have fewer requirements and can have a more practical design.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Alligators and crocodiles can be raised in captivity with "open cycle" or "closed cycle" methods.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Open cycle refers to programs that are concerned with the health of the wild population and are using captive rearing as a means to supplement the wild populations.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Closed-cycle operations are primarily concerned with harvest.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] In closed cycle operations, adult females are kept in captivity, and the eggs they lay are collected, incubated artificially, hatched, and the juveniles are grown to a certain size and harvested.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Closed cycle operations provide no incentive for conservation and are often unsuccessful because the cost of starting and managing the operation often outweighs the profits gained from products.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Although the cost of operating an open cycle operation is comparable to closed cycle, the goal of an open cycle operation is the overall health of the species, rather than economic profit.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Captive breeding and ranching operations provide more incentive to protect natural populations and are important contributors to the success of crocodilian populations.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Welfare concerns include the threat of crocodilian diseases such as caiman pox, adenoviral Hepatitis, mycoplasmosis, and chlamydiosis.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Crocodiles suffer from stress in confined spaces such as farms, leading to disease outbreaks.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Most crocodilians keep a body temperature within 28 and 33 degrees Celsius.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] On farms, body temperatures can reach 36 degrees Celsius, which affects the animals' immune system, and puts them at risk of various illnesses.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Another concern is for the cleanliness of the water in enclosures.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Many alligator farms in the United States have experienced losses due to *Sus scrofa* (feral swine) destroying nests.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Between 2001 and 2003, West Nile virus (WNV) infected and caused deaths resulting in economic loss in American alligators in Georgia, Florida, Louisiana, and Idaho.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] The disease is transmitted by mosquitoes.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] WNV has been found in Mexico at a crocodile farm in Ciudad del Carmen.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] The skin, most notably the underside, of alligators and crocodiles is of commercial value, so diseases of the skin need to be treated properly and effectively.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Commercial crocodile meat is widely consumed in Thailand, with a surge in popularity in 2022 as rising pork prices due to inflation led consumers to seek alternative protein sources.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] The meat is leaner than pork, attracting health-conscious individuals.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Since the 1950s, the Samutprakarn Crocodile Farm and Zoo have been supplying crocodile meat both domestically and internationally.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] As a commercial industry, local producers have established safe and hygienic processing methods, with approval from the Thai Ministry of Public Health.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] While information on this topic is limited, there have been no reported nationwide outbreaks of salmonellosis or typhoid linked to crocodile meat consumption in Thailand.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Crocodilian diseases vary between species.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Salmonellosis is common on some farms, and is acquired from infected food; it may also be spread by poor hygiene practices.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Chlamydia, (specifically *Chlamydophila psittaci*) can persist for years if not treated, for example with tetracycline.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Crocodilians may acquire mycobacteria from infected meat.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Illnesses affecting crocodilians include crocodile pox, which is caused by Parapoxvirus, affecting hatchlings and juveniles.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] It causes a brown residue to form around the eyes, oral cavity, and tail.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Caiman pox similarly causes white lesions around the eyes, oral cavity, and tail.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Adenoviral hepatitis causes organ failure and death.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Mycoplasmosis causes polyarthritis and pneumonia in crocodilians under the age of three.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Infected animals have swollen jaws and are unable to move.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Chlamydiosis has two forms that affects juveniles under one year of age.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] The first causes acute hepatitis, usually resulting in death.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] The other causes chronic bilateral conjunctivitis, usually resulting in blindness.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Parasitic infections include tapeworm cysts, *Trichinella spiralis nelsoni* in the meat of Nile crocodiles in Zimbabwe, and Coccidia.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] There have been reports of crocodiles escaping from farms during flooding.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] In 2013, approximately 15,000 crocodiles were released into the Limpopo River from flood gates at the nearby Rakwena Crocodile Farm.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Escaping is a common occurrence in Thailand, and the escaped crocodiles are often euthanized due to concerns for public safety.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Economic downturns which were exacerbated by the Covid-19 pandemic have led to the bankruptcy of many crocodile farms or the passing of their owners, resulting in inadequate maintenance of enclosures.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-farm] Without proper oversight, crocodiles may resort to cannibalism, increasing the risk of disease transmission, which could pose a public health threat if they escape into surrounding environments.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] There is no single method of alligator hunting.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] The use of a hook and line is the most common method.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] It involves securing a sturdy hook and line to a tree or pole in the ground.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] The hook is commonly baited with fish or chicken quarter.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] After the bait is taken, the hunter returns to draw in and dispatch the gator.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] Allowed methods of hunting vary by state, in South Carolina an alligator must be captured before being killed with either a handgun or bangstick.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] A bangstick is a specialized underwater firearm fired only when in direct contact with the target.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] Historically, unregulated hunting has led to dramatic decreases in alligator populations.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] In 1973 the American alligator was listed as endangered under the Endangered Species Act of 1973.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] The American alligator was listed as an endangered species in 1967 under a law that was a precursor to the Endangered Species Act of 1973.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] Since the species' recovery, alligator hunting programs have been established in the majority of U.S. states in the alligator's habitat range.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] The main products of alligator hunting are alligator meat and skin.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] Alligator skins have been harvested since the 1800s.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] Alligator skin was used in the manufacture of boots, belts, and saddles.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] In the early 1900s some states began the commercial tanning of alligator skin.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] The increased popularity of alligator leather led to the rise of alligator farming, now a $60 million industry.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] Following the global economic recession of 2008, demand for wild alligator skins declined dramatically.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-hunting] In the state of Louisiana the number of reported skins dropped from 35,625 to 9,139 in one year.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] In the United States, alligator meat is available for consumer purchase in specialty food stores, some grocery stores, and can also be mail ordered.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] A 100-gram (3+1⁄2-ounce) reference serving of alligator meat provides 600 kilojoules (143 kilocalories) of food energy, 29 grams of protein, 3 percent fat and 65 milligrams of cholesterol.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] It also contains a significant amount of phosphorus, potassium, vitamin B12, niacin and monounsaturated fatty acids.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] Alligator meat has been described as having a mild flavor and a firm texture.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] It tastes like quail, with a mildly fishy flavor, and is often chewy, depending on preparation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] Various methods of preparation and cooking exist, including tenderization, marination, deep frying, stewing, roasting, smoking and sauteeing.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] Alligator meat is used in dishes such as gumbo, and is used in traditional Louisiana Creole cuisine.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] Cuts from the animal used include meat from the animal's tail and backbone, which have been described as "the choicest cuts".
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] In the mid-1800s, alligator meat was used in some regional cuisines in parts of the Southern United States.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] During this time, it was used in dishes such as gumbo.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] Alligator eggs were a part of the cuisine in many areas of the Southern United States in the early 1900s.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] During this time people would harvest the eggs and then sell them as a source of income.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] Harvesting of wild alligator eggs is illegal without a proper permit; violators face serious fines and jail time.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] It is a matter of ongoing debate among Islamic scholars as to whether alligator meat is halal.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] Some consider alligator haram as a predatory animal.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] However, due to their aquatic nature, alligator meat is generally deemed halal, following the same tenets that apply to fish and other scaled aquatic life.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] Alligator meat is not explicitly condemned under Sharia.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] In 2010, the Archdiocese of New Orleans declared that alligator meat belongs to the "fish family" and, for the purposes of the Friday fast, is considered seafood, therefore allowing Catholics to consume it on Fridays and Ash Wednesday.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] In the United States, farming alligator for meat and hides is legal and practiced in states such as Georgia, South Carolina, Alabama, Arkansas, Mississippi, North Carolina, Florida, Louisiana, and Texas.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator-meat] Alligator hunting is legal in Arkansas, South Carolina, Louisiana, Florida, Georgia, and Texas.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] An **alligator**, or colloquially **gator**, is a large reptile in the genus ***Alligator*** of the family Alligatoridae in the order Crocodilia.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The two extant species are the American alligator (*A. mississippiensis*) and the Chinese alligator (*A. sinensis*).
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Additionally, several extinct species of alligator are known from fossil remains.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators first appeared during the late Eocene epoch about 37 million years ago.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The term "alligator" is likely an anglicized form of **el lagarto**, Spanish for "the lizard", which early Spanish explorers and settlers in Florida called the alligator.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Early English spellings of the name included *allagarta* and *alagarto*.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators are notable for their ability to inhabit climates that are considerably more temperate than those of most other crocodilians.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Although they generally prefer subtropical to tropical regions, they are also capable of surviving colder winters in the northern parts of their range.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators and caimans split in North America during the early Tertiary or late Cretaceous (about 53 million to 65 million years ago).
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The Chinese alligator split from the American alligator about 33 million years ago and probably descended from a lineage that crossed the Bering land bridge during the Neogene.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The modern American alligator is well represented in the fossil record of the Pleistocene.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The alligator's full mitochondrial genome was sequenced in the 1990s.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The full genome, published in 2014, suggests that the alligator evolved much more slowly than mammals and birds.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The genus *Alligator* belongs to the subfamily Alligatorinae, which is the sister taxon to Caimaninae (the caimans).
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Together, these two subfamilies form the family Alligatoridae.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The cladogram below shows the phylogeny of alligators.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] An average adult American alligator's weight and length is 360 kg (790 lb) and 4 m (13 ft), but they sometimes grow to 4.4 m (14 ft) long and weigh over 450 kg (990 lb).
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The largest ever recorded, found in Louisiana, measured 5.84 m (19.2 ft).
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The Chinese alligator is smaller, rarely exceeding 2.1 m (7 ft) in length.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Additionally, it weighs considerably less, with males rarely over 45 kg (100 lb).
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Adult alligators are black or dark olive-brown with white undersides, while juveniles have bright yellow or whitish stripes which sharply contrast against their dark hides, providing them additional camouflage amongst reeds and wetland grasses.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators commonly live up to 50 years, but there have been examples of alligators living over 70.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] One of the oldest recorded alligator lives was that of Saturn, an American alligator who was hatched in 1936 in Mississippi and spent nearly a decade in Germany before spending the majority of his life at the Moscow Zoo, where he died at the age of 83 or 84 on 22 May 2020.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Another one of the oldest lives on record is that of Muja, an American alligator who was brought as an adult specimen to the Belgrade Zoo in Serbia from Germany in 1937.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Although no valid records exist about his date of birth, as of 2012, he was in his 80s and possibly the oldest alligator living in captivity.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators are native only to the United States and China.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] American alligators are found in the southeast United States: all of Florida and Louisiana; the southern parts of Georgia, Alabama, and Mississippi; coastal South and North Carolina; East Texas, the southeast corner of Oklahoma, and the southern tip of Arkansas.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Louisiana has the largest alligator population.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The majority of American alligators inhabit Florida and Louisiana, with over a million alligators in each state.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Southern Florida is the only place where both alligators and crocodiles coexist.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] American alligators live in freshwater environments, such as ponds, wetlands, rivers, and lakes, as well as in brackish water.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] When they construct alligator holes in the wetlands, they increase plant diversity and provide habitat for other animals during droughts.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] They are, therefore, considered an important species for maintaining ecological diversity in wetlands.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Farther west, in Louisiana, heavy grazing by nutrias and muskrats is causing severe damage to coastal wetlands.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Large alligators feed extensively on nutrias, and provide a vital ecological service by reducing nutria numbers.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The Chinese alligator currently is found in only the Yangtze River valley and parts of adjacent provinces and is extremely endangered, with only a few dozen believed to be left in the wild.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Far more Chinese alligators live in zoos around the world than can be found in the wild.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Rockefeller Wildlife Refuge in southern Louisiana has several in captivity in an attempt to preserve the species.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Miami MetroZoo in Florida also has a breeding pair of Chinese alligators.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Large male alligators are solitary territorial animals.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Smaller alligators can often be found in large numbers close to each other.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The largest of the species (both males and females) defend prime territory; smaller alligators have a higher tolerance for other alligators within a similar size class.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators move on land by two forms of locomotion, referred to as "sprawl" and "high walk".
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The sprawl is a forward movement with the belly making contact with the ground and is used to transition to "high walk" or to slither over wet substrate into water.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The high walk is an up-on-four-limbs forward motion used for overland travel with the belly well up from the ground.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators have also been observed to rise up and balance on their hind legs and semi-step forward as part of a forward or upward lunge.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] However, they can not walk on their hind legs.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Although the alligator has a heavy body and a slow metabolism, it is capable of short bursts of speed, especially in very short lunges.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators' main prey are smaller animals they can kill and eat with a single bite.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] They may kill larger prey by grabbing it and dragging it into the water to drown.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators consume food that cannot be eaten in one bite by allowing it to rot or by biting and then performing a "death roll", spinning or convulsing wildly until bite-sized chunks are torn off.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Critical to the alligator's ability to initiate a death roll, the tail must flex to a significant angle relative to its body.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] An alligator with an immobilized tail cannot perform a death roll.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Most of the muscle in an alligator's jaw evolved to bite and grip prey.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The muscles that close the jaws are powerful, but the muscles for opening their jaws are weak.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] As a result, an adult human can hold an alligator's jaws shut bare-handed.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] It is common to use several wraps of duct tape to prevent an adult alligator from opening its jaws when being handled or transported.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators are generally timid towards humans and tend to walk or swim away if one approaches.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] This may encourage people to approach alligators and their nests, which can provoke the animals into attacking.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] In Florida, feeding wild alligators at any time is illegal.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] If fed, the alligators will eventually lose their fear of humans and will learn to associate humans with food.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The type of food eaten by alligators depends upon their age and size.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] When they are young, alligators eat fish, insects, snails, crustaceans, and worms.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] As they mature, progressively larger prey is taken, including larger fish, such as gar, turtles, and various mammals, particularly nutrias and muskrats, as well as birds, deer, and other reptiles.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Their stomachs also often contain gizzard stones.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] They will consume carrion if they are sufficiently hungry.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] In some cases, larger alligators are known to ambush dogs, Florida panthers, and black bears, making them the apex predator throughout their distribution.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] In this role as a top predator, it may determine the abundance of prey species, including turtles and nutrias.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators generally mature at a length of 1.8 m (6 ft).
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] In April and May, alligators form so-called "bellowing choruses".
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Large groups of animals bellow together for a few minutes a few times a day, usually one to three hours after sunrise.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The bellows of male American alligators are accompanied by powerful blasts of infrasound.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Another form of male display is a loud head-slap.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] In 2010, on spring nights alligators were found to gather in large numbers for group courtship, the so-called "alligator dances".
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] In summer, the female builds a nest of vegetation where the decomposition of the vegetation provides the heat needed to incubate the eggs.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The sex of the offspring is determined by the temperature in the nest and is fixed within seven to 21 days of the start of incubation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Incubation temperatures of 30 °C (86 °F) or lower produce a clutch of females; those of 34 °C (93 °F) or higher produce entirely males.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Nests constructed on leaves are hotter than those constructed on wet marsh, so the former tend to produce males and the latter, females.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The baby alligator's egg tooth helps it get out of its egg during hatching time.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The natural sex ratio at hatching is five females to one male.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Females hatched from eggs incubated at 30 °C (86 °F) weigh significantly more than males hatched from eggs incubated at 34 °C (93 °F).
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The mother defends the nest from predators and assists the hatchlings to water.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] She will provide protection to the young for about a year if they remain in the area.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Adult alligators regularly cannibalize younger individuals, though estimates of the rate of cannibalism vary widely.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] In the past, immediately following the outlawing of alligator hunting, populations rebounded quickly due to the suppressed number of adults preying upon juveniles, increasing survival among the young alligators.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators, much like birds, have been shown to exhibit unidirectional movement of air through their lungs.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Most other amniotes are believed to exhibit bidirectional, or tidal breathing.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] For a tidal breathing animal, such as a mammal, air flows into and out of the lungs through branching bronchi which terminate in small dead-end chambers called alveoli.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] As the alveoli represent dead-ends to flow, the inspired air must move back out the same way it came in.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] In contrast, air in alligator lungs makes a circuit, moving in only one direction through the parabronchi.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The air first enters the outer branch, moves through the parabronchi, and exits the lung through the inner branch.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Oxygen exchange takes place in extensive vasculature around the parabronchi.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The alligator has a similar digestive system to that of the crocodile, with minor differences in morphology and enzyme activity.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators have a two-part stomach, with the first smaller portion containing gastroliths.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] It is believed this portion of the stomach serves a similar function as it does in the gizzard of some species of birds, to aid in digestion.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The gastroliths work to grind up the meal as alligators will take large bites or swallow smaller prey whole.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] This process makes digestion and nutrient absorption easier once the food reaches the second portion of the stomach.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Once an alligator's meal has been processed it will move on to the second portion of the stomach which is highly acidic.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The acidity of the stomach has been observed to increase once digestion begins.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] This is due to the increase in CO2 concentration of the blood, resulting from the right to left shunting of the alligators heart.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The right to left shunt of the heart in alligators means the circulatory system will recirculate blood through the body instead of back to the lungs.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The re-circulation of blood leads to higher CO2 concentration as well as lower oxygen affinity.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] There is evidence to suggest that there is increased blood flow diverted to the stomach during digestion to facilitate an increase in CO2 concentration which aids in increasing gastric acid secretions during digestion.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The alligator's metabolism will also increase after a meal by up to four times its basal metabolic rate.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators also have highly folded mucosa in the lining of the intestines to further aid in the absorption of nutrients.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The folds result in greater surface area for the nutrients to be absorbed through.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators also have complex microbiomes that are not fully understood yet, but can be attributed to both benefits and costs to the animal.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] These microorganisms can be found in the high surface area of the mucosa folds of the intestines, as well as throughout the digestive tract.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Benefits include better total health and stronger immune system.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] However alligators are still vulnerable to microbial infections despite the immune boost from other microbiota.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] During brumation the process of digestion experiences changes due to the fasting most alligators experience during these periods of inactivity.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators that go long enough without a meal during brumation will begin a process called autophagy, where the animal begins to consume its fat reserves to maintain its body weight until it can acquire a sufficient meal.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] There is also fluctuation in the level of bacterial taxa populations in the alligator's microbial community between seasons which helps the alligator cope with different rates of feeding and activity.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Like other crocodilians, alligators have an armor of bony scutes.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The dermal bones are highly vascularised and aid in calcium balance, both to neutralize acids while the animal cannot breathe underwater and to provide calcium for eggshell formation.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators have muscular, flat tails that propel them while swimming.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The two kinds of white alligators are albino and leucistic.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] These alligators are practically impossible to find in the wild.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] They could survive only in captivity and are few in number.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] The Aquarium of the Americas in New Orleans has leucistic alligators found in a Louisiana swamp in 1987.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators are raised commercially for their meat and their skin, which when tanned is used for the manufacture of luggage, handbags, shoes, belts, and other leather items.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligators also provide economic benefits through the ecotourism industry.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Visitors may take swamp tours, in which alligators are a feature.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Their most important economic benefit to humans may be the control of nutrias and muskrats.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] Alligator meat is also consumed by humans.
[src:alligator-hunting/alligator] While there are rules of thumb for distinguishing alligators from crocodiles, all of them admit exceptions.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Previously part of French Louisiana and the Louisiana Purchase, the Territory of Arkansas was admitted to the Union as the 25th state on June 15, 1836.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Much of the Delta had been developed for cotton plantations, and landowners there largely depended on enslaved African Americans' labor.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In 1861, Arkansas seceded from the United States and joined the Confederate States of America during the American Civil War.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] On returning to the Union in 1868, Arkansas continued to suffer economically, due to its overreliance on the large-scale plantation economy.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Cotton remained the leading commodity crop, and the cotton market declined.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Because farmers and businessmen did not diversify and there was little industrial investment, the state fell behind in economic opportunity.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In the late 19th century, the state instituted various Jim Crow laws to disenfranchise and segregate the African-American population.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] During the civil rights movement of the 1950s and 1960s, Arkansas, particularly Little Rock, was a major battleground in efforts to integrate schools.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Following World War II in the 1940s, Arkansas began to diversify its economy and see prosperity.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] During the 1960s, the state became the base of the Walmart corporation, the world's largest company by revenue, headquartered in Bentonville.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas is the 29th largest by area and the 33rd most populous state, with a population of just over three million at the 2020 census.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The capital and most populous city is Little Rock, in the central part of the state, a hub for transportation, business, culture, and government.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The northwestern corner of the state, namely the Fayetteville–Springdale–Rogers Metropolitan Area, is a population, education, cultural, and economic center.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The Fort Smith Metropolitan Area is also an economic center and is known for its historic sites related to western expansion and the persecution of Native Americans.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In the 21st century, Arkansas's economy is based on service industries, aircraft, poultry, steel, and tourism, along with important commodity crops of cotton, soybeans and rice.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The state supports a network of public universities and colleges, including two major university systems: Arkansas State University System and University of Arkansas System.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas's culture is observable in museums, theaters, novels, television shows, restaurants, and athletic venues across the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The name *Arkansas* initially applied to the Arkansas River.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] It derives from a French term, *Arcansas*, their plural term for their transliteration of *akansa*, an Algonquian term for the Quapaw people, which is believed to translate to "south wind people".
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] These were a Dhegiha Siouan-speaking people who settled in Arkansas around the 13th century.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] *Kansa* is likely also the root term for Kansas, which was named after the related Kaw people.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The name has been pronounced and spelled in various ways.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In 1881, the state legislature defined the official pronunciation of Arkansas as having the final "s" be silent (as it would be in French).
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] A dispute had arisen between the state's two senators over the pronunciation issue.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] One favored /ˈɑːrkənsɔː/ (*AR-kən-saw*), the other /ɑːrˈkænzəs/ (*ar-KAN-zəs*).
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In 2007, the state legislature passed a non-binding resolution declaring that the possessive form of the state's name is *Arkansas's*, which the state government has increasingly followed.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Before European settlement of North America, Arkansas was inhabited by indigenous peoples for thousands of years.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The Caddo, Osage, and Quapaw peoples encountered European explorers.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The first of these Europeans was Spanish explorer Hernando de Soto in 1541, who crossed the Mississippi and marched across central Arkansas and the Ozark Mountains.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] After finding nothing he considered of value and encountering native resistance the entire way, he and his men returned to the Mississippi River, where de Soto fell ill.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] From his deathbed, he ordered his men to massacre all the men of the nearby village of Anilco, whom he feared had been plotting with a powerful polity down the Mississippi River, *Quigualtam*.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] His men obeyed and did not stop with the men, but were said to have massacred women and children as well.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] He died the following day in what is believed to be the vicinity of modern-day McArthur, Arkansas, in May 1542.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] His body was weighted down with sand, and he was consigned to a watery grave in the Mississippi River under cover of darkness by his men.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] De Soto had attempted to deceive the native population into thinking he was an immortal deity, sun of the sun, in order to forestall attack by outraged Native Americans on his by then weakened and bedraggled army.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In order to keep the ruse up, his men informed the locals that de Soto had ascended into the sky.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] His will at the time of his death listed "four Indian slaves, three horses and 700 hogs," which were auctioned off.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The starving men, who had been living off maize stolen from natives, immediately began butchering the hogs and later, under the command of former aide-de-camp Moscoso, attempted an overland return to Mexico.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] They made it as far as Texas before running into territory too dry for maize farming and too thinly populated to sustain themselves by stealing food from the locals.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The expedition promptly backtracked to Arkansas.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] After building a small fleet of boats, they then headed down the Mississippi River and eventually on to Mexico by water.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Later explorers included the French Jacques Marquette and Louis Jolliet in 1673, and Frenchmen Robert La Salle and Henri de Tonti in 1681.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Tonti established Arkansas Post at a Quapaw village in 1686, making it the first European settlement in the territory.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The early Spanish or French explorers of the state gave it its name, which is probably a phonetic spelling of the Illinois tribe's name for the Quapaw people, who lived downriver from them.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The name Arkansas has been pronounced and spelled in a variety of fashions.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The region was organized as the Territory of Arkansaw on July 4, 1819, and was admitted to the United States as the state of Arkansas on June 15, 1836.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The name was historically /ˈɑːrkənsɔː/, /ɑːrˈkænzəs/, and several other variants.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Historically and modernly, the people of Arkansas call themselves either "Arkansans" or "Arkansawyers".
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Citizens of the state of Kansas often pronounce the Arkansas River as /ɑːrˈkænzəs/, in a manner similar to the common pronunciation of the name of their state.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Settlers, such as fur trappers, moved to Arkansas in the early 18th century.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] These people used Arkansas Post as a home base and entrepôt.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] During the colonial period, Arkansas changed hands between France and Spain following the Seven Years' War, although neither showed interest in the remote settlement of Arkansas Post.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In April 1783, Arkansas saw its only battle of the American Revolutionary War, a brief siege of the post by British Captain James Colbert with the assistance of the Choctaw and Chickasaw.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Napoleon Bonaparte sold French Louisiana to the United States in 1803, including all of Arkansas, in a transaction known today as the Louisiana Purchase.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] French soldiers remained as a garrison at Arkansas Post.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Following the purchase, the balanced give-and-take relationship between settlers and Native Americans began to change all along the frontier, including in Arkansas.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Following a controversy over allowing slavery in the territory, the Territory of Arkansas was organized on July 4, 1819.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Gradual emancipation in Arkansas was struck down by one vote, the Speaker of the House Henry Clay, allowing Arkansas to organize as a slave territory.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Slavery became a wedge issue in Arkansas, forming a geographic divide that remained for decades.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Owners and operators of the cotton plantation economy in southeast Arkansas firmly supported slavery, as they perceived slave labor as the best or "only" economically viable method of harvesting their commodity crops.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The "hill country" of northwest Arkansas was unable to grow cotton and relied on a cash-scarce, subsistence farming economy.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] As European Americans settled throughout the East Coast and into the Midwest, in the 1830s the United States government forced the removal of many Native American tribes to Arkansas and Indian Territory west of the Mississippi River.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Additional Native American removals began in earnest during the territorial period, with final Quapaw removal complete by 1833 as they were pushed into Indian Territory.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The capital was relocated from Arkansas Post to Little Rock in 1821, during the territorial period.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] When Arkansas applied for statehood, the slavery issue was again raised in Washington, D.C.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Congress eventually approved the Arkansas Constitution after a 25-hour session, admitting Arkansas on June 15, 1836, as the 25th state and the 13th slave state, having a population of about 60,000.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas struggled with taxation to support its new state government, a problem made worse by a state banking scandal and worse yet by the Panic of 1837.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In early antebellum Arkansas, the southeast Arkansas slave-based economy developed rapidly.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] On the eve of the American Civil War in 1860, enslaved African Americans numbered 111,115 people, just over 25% of the state's population.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] A plantation system based largely on cotton agriculture developed that, after the war, kept the state and region behind the nation for decades.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The wealth developed among planters of southeast Arkansas caused a political rift between the northwest and southeast.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Many politicians were elected to office from the Family, the dominant Democratic political force in antebellum Arkansas.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Residents generally wanted to avoid a civil war.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] When the Gulf states seceded in early 1861, delegates to a convention called to determine whether Arkansas should secede referred the question back to the voters for a referendum to be held in August.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas did not secede until Abraham Lincoln demanded Arkansas troops be sent to Fort Sumter to quell the rebellion there and Governor Henry Rector refused.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] On May 6, the members of the state convention, having been recalled by the convention president, voted to terminate Arkansas's membership in the Union and join the Confederate States of America.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas held a very important position for the Rebels, as it controlled the Mississippi River and the surrounding Southern states.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The bloody Battle of Wilson's Creek just across the border in Missouri shocked many Arkansans who thought the war would be a quick and decisive Southern victory.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Battles early in the war took place in northwest Arkansas, including the Battle of Cane Hill, Battle of Pea Ridge, and Battle of Prairie Grove.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Union general Samuel Curtis swept across the state to Helena in the Delta in 1862.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Little Rock was captured the following year.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The government shifted the state Confederate capital from Hot Springs to Washington from 1863 to 1865, for the remainder of the war.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Throughout the state, guerrilla warfare ravaged the countryside and destroyed cities.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Passion for the Confederate cause waned after implementation of programs such as the draft, high taxes, and martial law.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Under the Military Reconstruction Act, Congress declared Arkansas restored to the Union in June 1868, after the Legislature accepted the 14th Amendment.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Republican-dominated Reconstruction legislatures expanded civil rights by establishing the South's first comprehensive state-supported public education systems and by establishing universal male suffrage, regardless of race.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] These conventions and governments, which temporarily disenfranchised former Confederate officials, enacted these reforms.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The State soon came under the control of the Radical Republicans and Unionists, and, led by Governor Powell Clayton, they presided over a time of great upheaval as Confederate sympathizers and the Ku Klux Klan fought the new developments, particularly voting rights for African Americans.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In 1874, the Brooks-Baxter War, a political struggle between factions of the Republican Party shook Little Rock and the state governorship.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] It was settled only when President Ulysses S.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Grant ordered Joseph Brooks to disperse his militant supporters.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Following the Brooks-Baxter War, a new state constitution was ratified, re-enfranchising former Confederates and effectively ending Reconstruction.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In 1881, the Arkansas state legislature enacted a bill adopting an official pronunciation of the state's name to combat a simmering controversy.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] After Reconstruction, the state began to receive more immigrants and migrants.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Chinese, Italian, and Syrian men were recruited for farm labor in the developing Delta region.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] None of these nationalities stayed long at farm labor; the Chinese especially, as they quickly became small merchants in towns around the Delta.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Many Chinese became such successful merchants in small towns that they were able to educate their children at college.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Construction of railroads enabled more farmers to get their products to market.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] It also brought new development into different parts of the state, including the Ozarks, where some areas were developed as resorts.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In a few years at the end of the 19th century, for instance, Eureka Springs in Carroll County grew to 10,000 people, rapidly becoming a tourist destination and the state's fourth-largest city.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] It featured newly constructed, elegant resort hotels and spas planned around its natural springs, considered to have healthful properties.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The town's attractions included horse racing and other entertainment.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] It appealed to a wide variety of classes, becoming almost as popular as Hot Springs.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In the late 1880s, the worsening agricultural depression catalyzed Populist and third party movements, leading to interracial coalitions.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Struggling to stay in power, in the 1890s the Democrats in Arkansas followed other Southern states in passing legislation and constitutional amendments that disfranchised blacks and poor whites.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In 1891 state legislators passed a requirement for a literacy test, knowing it would exclude many blacks and whites.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] At the time, more than 25% of the population could neither read nor write.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In 1892, they amended the state constitution to require a poll tax and more complex residency requirements, both of which adversely affected poor people and sharecroppers, forcing most blacks and many poor whites from voter rolls.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] By 1900 the Democratic Party expanded use of the white primary in county and state elections, further denying blacks a part in the political process.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Only in the primary was there any competition among candidates, as Democrats held all the power.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The state was a Democratic one-party state for decades, until after passage of the federal Civil Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965 to enforce constitutional rights.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Between 1905 and 1911, Arkansas began to receive a small immigration of German, Slovak, and Scots-Irish from Europe.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The German and Slovak peoples settled in the eastern part of the state known as the Prairie, and the Irish founded small communities in the southeast part of the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The Germans were mostly Lutheran and the Slovaks were primarily Catholic.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The Irish were mostly Protestant from Ulster, of Scots and Northern Borders descent.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Some early 20th-century immigration included people from eastern Europe.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Together, these immigrants made the Delta more diverse than the rest of the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In the same years, some black migrants moved into the area because of opportunities to develop the bottomlands and own their own property.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Black sharecroppers began to try to organize a farmers' union after World War I.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] They were seeking better conditions of payment and accounting from white landowners of the area cotton plantations.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Whites resisted any change and often tried to break up their meetings.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] On September 30, 1919, two white men, including a local deputy, tried to break up a meeting of black sharecroppers who were trying to organize a farmers' union.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] After a white deputy was killed in a confrontation with guards at the meeting, word spread to town and around the area.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Hundreds of whites from Phillips and neighboring areas rushed to suppress the blacks, and started attacking blacks at large.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Governor Charles Hillman Brough requested federal troops to stop what was called the Elaine massacre.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] White mobs spread throughout the county, killing an estimated 237 blacks before most of the violence was suppressed after October 1.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The governor accompanied the troops to the scene; President Woodrow Wilson had approved their use.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The Great Mississippi Flood of 1927 flooded the areas along the Ouachita Rivers along with many other rivers.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Based on the order of President Franklin D.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Roosevelt given shortly after the Empire of Japan's attack on Pearl Harbor, nearly 16,000 Japanese Americans were forcibly removed from the West Coast of the United States and incarcerated in two internment camps in the Arkansas Delta.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The Rohwer Camp in Desha County operated from September 1942 to November 1945 and at its peak interned 8,475 prisoners.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The Jerome War Relocation Center in Drew County operated from October 1942 to June 1944 and held about 8,000.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] After the Supreme Court ruled segregation in public schools unconstitutional in *Brown*v.*Board of Education of Topeka, Kansas* (1954), some students worked to integrate schools in the state.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The Little Rock Nine brought Arkansas to national attention in 1957 when the federal government had to intervene to protect African-American students trying to integrate a high school in the capital.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Governor Orval Faubus had ordered the Arkansas National Guard to help segregationists prevent nine African-American students from enrolling at Little Rock's Central High School.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] After attempting three times to contact Faubus, President Dwight D.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Eisenhower sent 1,000 troops from the active-duty 101st Airborne Division to escort and protect the African-American students as they entered school on September 25, 1957.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In defiance of federal court orders to integrate, the governor and city of Little Rock decided to close the high schools for the remainder of the school year.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] By the fall of 1959, the Little Rock high schools were completely integrated.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas borders Louisiana to the south, Texas to the southwest, Oklahoma to the west, Missouri to the north, and Tennessee and Mississippi to the east.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The United States Census Bureau classifies Arkansas as a southern state, sub-categorized among the West South Central States.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The Mississippi River forms most of its eastern border, except in Clay and Greene counties, where the St.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Francis River forms the western boundary of the Missouri Bootheel, and in many places where the channel of the Mississippi has meandered (or been straightened by man) from its original 1836 course.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas can generally be split into two halves, the highlands in the northwest and the lowlands of the southeast.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The highlands are part of the Southern Interior Highlands, including The Ozarks and the Ouachita Mountains.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The southern lowlands include the Gulf Coastal Plain and the Arkansas Delta.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] This split can yield to a regional division into northwest, southwest, northeast, southeast, and central Arkansas.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] These regions are broad and not defined along county lines.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas has seven distinct natural regions: the Ozark Mountains, Ouachita Mountains, Arkansas River Valley, Gulf Coastal Plain, Crowley's Ridge, and the Arkansas Delta, with Central Arkansas sometimes included as a blend of multiple regions.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The southeastern part of Arkansas along the Mississippi Alluvial Plain is sometimes called the Arkansas Delta.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] This region is a flat landscape of rich alluvial soils formed by repeated flooding of the adjacent Mississippi.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Farther from the river, in the southeastern part of the state, the Grand Prairie has a more undulating landscape.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The Delta region is bisected by a geological formation known as Crowley's Ridge.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] A narrow band of rolling hills, Crowley's Ridge rises 250 to 500 feet (76 to 152 m) above the surrounding alluvial plain and underlies many of eastern Arkansas's major towns.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Northwest Arkansas is part of the Ozark Plateau including the Ozark Mountains, to the south are the Ouachita Mountains, and these regions are divided by the Arkansas River; the southern and eastern parts of Arkansas are called the Lowlands.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] These mountain ranges are part of the U.S.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Interior Highlands region, the only major mountainous region between the Rocky Mountains and the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The state's highest point is Mount Magazine in the Ouachita Mountains, which is 2,753 feet (839 m) above sea level.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas is home to many caves, such as Blanchard Springs Caverns.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The State Archeologist has catalogued more than 43,000 Native American living, hunting and tool-making sites, many of them Pre-Columbian burial mounds and rock shelters.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Crater of Diamonds State Park near Murfreesboro is the world's only diamond-bearing site accessible to the public for digging.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas is home to a dozen Wilderness Areas totaling 158,444 acres (641.20 km2).
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] These areas are set aside for outdoor recreation and are open to hunting, fishing, hiking, and primitive camping.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] No mechanized vehicles nor developed campgrounds are allowed in these areas.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas has many rivers, lakes, and reservoirs within or along its borders.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Major tributaries to the Mississippi River include the Arkansas River, the White River, and the St.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The Arkansas is fed by the Mulberry and Fourche La Fave Rivers in the Arkansas River Valley, which is also home to Lake Dardanelle.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The Buffalo, Little Red, Black and Cache Rivers are all tributaries to the White River, which also empties into the Mississippi.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Bayou Bartholomew and the Saline, Little Missouri, and Caddo Rivers are all tributaries to the Ouachita River in south Arkansas, which empties into the Mississippi in Louisiana.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The Red River briefly forms the state's boundary with Texas.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas has few natural lakes and many reservoirs, such as Bull Shoals Lake, Lake Ouachita, Greers Ferry Lake, Millwood Lake, Beaver Lake, Norfork Lake, DeGray Lake, and Lake Conway.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas's mix of warm temperate moist forest and subtropical bottomland is divided into three broad ecoregions: the *Ozark, Ouachita-Appalachian Forests*, the *Mississippi Alluvial and Southeast USA Coastal Plains*, and the *Southeastern USA Plains*.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The state is further divided into seven subregions: the Arkansas Valley, Boston Mountains, Mississippi Alluvial Plain, Mississippi Valley Loess Plain, Ozark Highlands, Ouachita Mountains, and the South Central Plains.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] A 2010 United States Forest Service survey determined 18,720,000 acres (7,580,000 ha) of Arkansas's land is forestland, or 56% of the state's total area.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Dominant species in Arkansas's forests include *Quercus* (oak), *Carya* (hickory), *Pinus echinata* (shortleaf pine) and *Pinus taeda* (loblolly pine).
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas's plant life varies with its climate and elevation.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The pine belt stretching from the Arkansas delta to Texas consists of dense oak-hickory-pine growth.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Lumbering and paper milling activity is active throughout the region.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] In eastern Arkansas, one can find *Taxodium*(cypress), *Quercus nigra* (water oaks), and hickories with their roots submerged in the Mississippi Valley bayous indicative of the Deep South.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Saw palmetto and needle palm both range into Arkansas.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Nearby Crowley's Ridge is the only home of the tulip tree in the state, and generally hosts more northeastern plant life such as the beech tree.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The northwestern highlands are covered in an oak-hickory mixture, with Ozark white cedars, *cornus* (dogwoods), and *Cercis canadensis* (redbuds) also present.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The higher peaks in the Arkansas River Valley play host to scores of ferns, including the *Physematium scopulinum* and *Adiantum* (maidenhair fern) on Mount Magazine.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] The white-tailed deer is the official state mammal.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] Arkansas generally has a humid subtropical climate.
[src:alligator-hunting/arkansas-p01] While not bordering the Gulf of Mexico, Arkansas, is still close enough to the warm, large body of water for it to influence the weather in the state.
